1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:18,151
A makeover project
for your most unhinged leftovers.

2
00:00:18,218 --> 00:00:22,088
The best chefs in Korea will
turn your fridge inside out.

3
00:00:22,155 --> 00:00:24,124
The classy cooking show has returned.

4
00:00:24,190 --> 00:00:26,693
<i>-Chef & My Fridge!</i>
<i>-My Fridge!</i>

5
00:00:27,594 --> 00:00:28,661
Welcome.

6
00:00:28,728 --> 00:00:29,896
-Hello.
-Hello.

7
00:00:29,963 --> 00:00:31,898
Everyone is looking great as always.

8
00:00:31,965 --> 00:00:35,435
We have a new chef here with us.

9
00:00:36,002 --> 00:00:38,304
<i>I'll take your Michelin star today.</i>

10
00:00:38,371 --> 00:00:40,673
Cooking Maniac survives.

11
00:00:41,808 --> 00:00:43,043
COOKING MANIAC SURVIVES

12
00:00:43,109 --> 00:00:44,844
A CHEF WHO USES
TRADITIONAL KOREAN INGREDIENTS

13
00:00:44,911 --> 00:00:47,781
<i>A chef from Australia that loves Korea.</i>

14
00:00:47,847 --> 00:00:49,682
<i>Please welcome Chef Joseph Lidgerwood!</i>

15
00:00:49,749 --> 00:00:52,252
Can you look into the camera
and say hi to the viewers?

16
00:00:52,318 --> 00:00:54,554
Yes, where is it? Right here.

17
00:00:55,688 --> 00:00:57,457
-What now? Say hello?
-Yes, say hello.

18
00:00:58,958 --> 00:01:00,760
Hello, my name is Joseph.

19
00:01:00,827 --> 00:01:02,862
-Welcome to the show.
-It's great to meet you.

20
00:01:02,929 --> 00:01:05,231
Welcome to the show.

21
00:01:06,032 --> 00:01:07,300
He's another good-looking guy.

22
00:01:07,367 --> 00:01:08,735
Lots of guys with good vibes here.

23
00:01:08,802 --> 00:01:11,938
You were one of the White Spoons
in <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

24
00:01:12,005 --> 00:01:13,473
White Spoon.

25
00:01:14,607 --> 00:01:17,410
Back then, the one who beat you was…

26
00:01:17,477 --> 00:01:19,579
My gosh. It was Nam-no.

27
00:01:19,646 --> 00:01:23,950
-Nam-no won?
-He won against a Michelin two-star chef.

28
00:01:24,017 --> 00:01:28,488
I can't believe this.
You lost against Nam-no?

29
00:01:28,555 --> 00:01:32,025
-It's hard to understand.
-A Michelin two-star chef?

30
00:01:32,092 --> 00:01:33,226
Oh, no.

31
00:01:33,293 --> 00:01:34,928
You should be on that show too.

32
00:01:34,994 --> 00:01:36,996
-Should I?
-I think you qualify.

33
00:01:37,063 --> 00:01:38,832
-You qualify.
-Yes.

34
00:01:38,898 --> 00:01:41,101
-Poong?
-I mean, what happened?

35
00:01:41,167 --> 00:01:42,535
-Chef Joseph.
-Yes?

36
00:01:42,602 --> 00:01:46,439
The more it went on,
the more traumatized I was.

37
00:01:46,506 --> 00:01:47,974
You were stressed out.

38
00:01:48,041 --> 00:01:51,377
Whenever I went to a convenience store
or got on the bus…

39
00:01:51,444 --> 00:01:52,645
Even at a convenience store!

40
00:01:52,712 --> 00:01:57,584
I saw him everywhere I went,
so I was traumatized.

41
00:01:57,650 --> 00:01:59,452
And you have that laughter.

42
00:02:00,920 --> 00:02:02,122
He's always on TV.

43
00:02:02,188 --> 00:02:04,624
He has such a cheeky laughter.

44
00:02:04,691 --> 00:02:08,895
If we let you two compete again,
do you think you can win?

45
00:02:08,962 --> 00:02:11,164
I feel confident. I am.

46
00:02:11,231 --> 00:02:12,499
But only if Chef Nam-no accepts it.

47
00:02:12,565 --> 00:02:14,033
-Yes or no?
-Will you say yes?

48
00:02:14,100 --> 00:02:17,036
-I'd feel too bad if I won twice.
-Come on!

49
00:02:17,103 --> 00:02:18,838
ANOTHER TRAUMA

50
00:02:19,405 --> 00:02:21,641
-So he'll win again today?
-I see.

51
00:02:21,708 --> 00:02:24,010
Whoa, Chef Joseph said he was

52
00:02:24,077 --> 00:02:28,314
-more annoyed with Fabri than Nam-no.
-What?

53
00:02:28,381 --> 00:02:29,649
Me? Why?

54
00:02:29,716 --> 00:02:32,685
Chef Fabri, you came
on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> first, right?

55
00:02:32,752 --> 00:02:34,787
-Yes.
-But the thing is,

56
00:02:34,854 --> 00:02:37,757
he chose to call Chef Joseph and say,

57
00:02:37,824 --> 00:02:39,325
"I'm going on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>."

58
00:02:39,392 --> 00:02:42,362
-"What happened with you?"
-I see. He was like,

59
00:02:42,428 --> 00:02:44,497
-"Why aren't you here?"
-That's so annoying.

60
00:02:44,564 --> 00:02:47,267
I just made a simple call

61
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:49,302
-because I was curious.
-You were curious.

62
00:02:49,369 --> 00:02:52,839
I worried we might have
similar characters.

63
00:02:52,906 --> 00:02:55,775
-I don't know.
-Your characters?

64
00:02:55,842 --> 00:02:57,410
You're quite ambitious.

65
00:02:57,477 --> 00:03:00,747
The production crew
didn't just ask me to be here.

66
00:03:01,314 --> 00:03:04,350
They're over there.

67
00:03:04,417 --> 00:03:05,418
The production crew's idea.

68
00:03:05,485 --> 00:03:09,289
Why did you have to call Joseph too?

69
00:03:09,355 --> 00:03:12,625
There were no foreign chefs,
so someone had to be here.

70
00:03:12,692 --> 00:03:15,461
-Probably me or Joseph.
-Will it be Fabri or Joseph?

71
00:03:15,528 --> 00:03:17,463
I wanted to confirm that.

72
00:03:17,530 --> 00:03:19,599
There's a fight over the position.

73
00:03:19,666 --> 00:03:21,167
It's fierce.

74
00:03:21,234 --> 00:03:24,704
It's time to invite today's fridge owners.

75
00:03:24,771 --> 00:03:29,609
Our guests today are two legendary stars.

76
00:03:29,676 --> 00:03:32,011
Please welcome the fridge owners!

77
00:03:32,078 --> 00:03:33,213
Come on out!

78
00:03:34,781 --> 00:03:36,549
WHO WILL IT BE?

79
00:03:36,616 --> 00:03:38,618
Today's fridge owners!

80
00:03:39,118 --> 00:03:41,487
Today's fridge owners!

81
00:03:41,554 --> 00:03:45,425
Two Korean national team soccer players,
Kim Nam-il and Lee Dong-gook!

82
00:03:45,491 --> 00:03:47,527
-Welcome.
-Welcome.

83
00:03:47,594 --> 00:03:49,462
Come on in.

84
00:03:49,529 --> 00:03:50,897
-Have a seat.
-Welcome.

85
00:03:50,964 --> 00:03:52,532
-Have a seat.
-Welcome.

86
00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:54,734
-Why are you so kind?
-What?

87
00:03:54,801 --> 00:03:57,403
I'm always kind to the guests.

88
00:03:57,470 --> 00:03:59,272
You two are here as guests.

89
00:03:59,339 --> 00:04:01,140
He must be acting different from usual.

90
00:04:01,207 --> 00:04:03,476
-Have a seat.
-Take a seat and relax.

91
00:04:03,543 --> 00:04:07,747
-Today's guests are related to Jung-hwan.
-You're right.

92
00:04:07,814 --> 00:04:11,684
There's a reason why we invited
these two on the show today.

93
00:04:11,751 --> 00:04:16,155
The Gentlemen's League Season Four
<i>has recently launched</i>.

94
00:04:16,222 --> 00:04:18,558
<i>Nam-il, Dong-gook, Jung-hwan,</i>

95
00:04:18,625 --> 00:04:21,561
<i>and Park Hang-seo,</i>
<i>four of them are on the show.</i>

96
00:04:21,628 --> 00:04:25,298
<i>We've drafted 14 players each.</i>

97
00:04:25,365 --> 00:04:31,070
And the winning team will get a chance to
watch the 2026 FIFA World Cup in person.

98
00:04:31,137 --> 00:04:34,307
The entire winning squad will
go and watch the 2026 World Cup.

99
00:04:34,374 --> 00:04:36,809
On the other hand,
the team that comes last

100
00:04:36,876 --> 00:04:39,379
will have to be dissolved.

101
00:04:39,445 --> 00:04:40,446
-Dissolved?
-That's harsh.

102
00:04:40,513 --> 00:04:43,750
-We don't know what will happen.
-It's like <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

103
00:04:43,816 --> 00:04:46,919
These three soccer players
aren't just talented players.

104
00:04:46,986 --> 00:04:50,690
They were also popular
thanks to their good looks.

105
00:04:50,757 --> 00:04:53,993
One website recently released a ranking

106
00:04:54,060 --> 00:04:58,131
-on the best-looking soccer players.
-Really?

107
00:04:58,197 --> 00:04:59,999
The three men here took

108
00:05:00,066 --> 00:05:03,436
first place, third place,
and fourth place.

109
00:05:03,503 --> 00:05:05,204
-Who took second place?
-Yes.

110
00:05:05,271 --> 00:05:07,440
The second place winner still plays.

111
00:05:07,507 --> 00:05:11,377
It was Jeong Seung-won of FC Seoul.

112
00:05:11,444 --> 00:05:14,113
Let's take a look and find out
why people voted for them.

113
00:05:14,180 --> 00:05:16,282
You'll find them behind me.

114
00:05:17,283 --> 00:05:20,086
I think they were chosen
thanks to these pictures.

115
00:05:20,153 --> 00:05:22,488
-Look at those guys.
-That's not you.

116
00:05:22,555 --> 00:05:25,258
-Who are you? Where's that person?
-No, that's not me.

117
00:05:25,325 --> 00:05:27,060
<i>-Where did he go?</i>
<i>-Don't think of my past.</i>

118
00:05:27,126 --> 00:05:29,162
<i>-My gosh.</i>
<i>-You're right.</i>

119
00:05:29,228 --> 00:05:31,364
But he's more like Mario now.

120
00:05:31,431 --> 00:05:32,799
MARIO, LOL

121
00:05:32,865 --> 00:05:36,235
-He'll look like Mario with a mustache.
-Yes, he just needs a mustache.

122
00:05:36,302 --> 00:05:39,005
What has life done to Jung-hwan?

123
00:05:39,572 --> 00:05:40,940
HE SHOULD'VE TRIED
TO GO AGAINST TIME

124
00:05:41,007 --> 00:05:42,108
Tell me about it.

125
00:05:42,175 --> 00:05:45,812
-My gosh.
-You're right. I remember those days.

126
00:05:45,878 --> 00:05:48,648
<i>He was known</i>
<i>as Gang Dong-won on the pitch.</i>

127
00:05:48,715 --> 00:05:50,416
-I can see it.
-If you say that,

128
00:05:50,483 --> 00:05:51,818
-he'll think it's true.
-I can see it.

129
00:05:51,884 --> 00:05:54,520
-His profile is just like Dong-won's.
-See?

130
00:05:54,587 --> 00:05:56,656
-She can say that.
-Do you want an autograph?

131
00:05:56,723 --> 00:05:57,857
GOOD GRIEF

132
00:05:57,924 --> 00:06:00,426
-Listen to that guy.
-Come on.

133
00:06:00,493 --> 00:06:03,563
He's acting so silly.

134
00:06:03,629 --> 00:06:05,431
They both got nice pictures,

135
00:06:05,498 --> 00:06:08,434
but that was
while I was serving in the army.

136
00:06:08,501 --> 00:06:10,470
You looked best back then.

137
00:06:11,471 --> 00:06:12,472
Please put up another picture.

138
00:06:12,538 --> 00:06:15,575
Even back then, Jung-hwan was very…

139
00:06:15,641 --> 00:06:18,911
He tried to get on TV since those days.

140
00:06:18,978 --> 00:06:21,848
He'd wear earrings and stuff.

141
00:06:21,914 --> 00:06:26,185
He even grew out his hair
and wore a headband too.

142
00:06:26,252 --> 00:06:30,323
He only became a soccer player
to get on TV.

143
00:06:31,858 --> 00:06:32,859
Tell me about it.

144
00:06:32,925 --> 00:06:35,228
He took advantage of soccer
to get into TV.

145
00:06:35,294 --> 00:06:36,996
He's good at getting on your nerves.

146
00:06:37,063 --> 00:06:39,832
-So he wasn't serious about soccer.
-Right.

147
00:06:39,899 --> 00:06:41,534
When he walked out on the pitch,

148
00:06:41,601 --> 00:06:44,904
-the pitch would reek of his cologne.
-Really?

149
00:06:44,971 --> 00:06:47,774
The pitch reeked of cologne?

150
00:06:47,840 --> 00:06:49,308
We were often roommates

151
00:06:49,375 --> 00:06:51,444
when we were on the national team.

152
00:06:51,511 --> 00:06:54,313
He'd start spraying cologne
even before he went out.

153
00:06:54,380 --> 00:06:56,916
-He pretty much showered himself.
-He showered himself?

154
00:06:56,983 --> 00:06:59,152
-He'd shower himself?
-He used it like a face mist.

155
00:06:59,218 --> 00:07:01,687
You were going out to sweat anyway.
Why did you shower yourself?

156
00:07:01,754 --> 00:07:03,289
It was a part of my routine!

157
00:07:03,356 --> 00:07:05,291
That was your routine?

158
00:07:05,358 --> 00:07:06,893
So I see.

159
00:07:06,959 --> 00:07:11,030
When Nam-il played,
he was nicknamed the vacuum cleaner.

160
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:14,167
He swept his way all over the midfield.

161
00:07:14,233 --> 00:07:16,102
Did he have any other nicknames?

162
00:07:16,169 --> 00:07:18,471
-He had lots. No Turning Back.
-No Turning Back?

163
00:07:18,538 --> 00:07:21,374
And K-Hot Temper.

164
00:07:21,441 --> 00:07:22,442
-K-Hot Temper?
-K-Hot Temper?

165
00:07:22,508 --> 00:07:24,544
I'm glad he was with us.
If he were with them,

166
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:27,447
-he would've caused so much headache.
-Yes.

167
00:07:27,513 --> 00:07:30,716
-That's what he was like.
-I'm glad he's on our side.

168
00:07:30,783 --> 00:07:32,518
-It's a relief.
-You should be relieved.

169
00:07:32,585 --> 00:07:34,454
-Yes, I said it.
-You need to know that.

170
00:07:34,520 --> 00:07:37,390
If I were on a different team,

171
00:07:37,457 --> 00:07:39,258
I could've made you retire sooner.

172
00:07:39,325 --> 00:07:40,793
THE ENEMY VACUUM CLEANER

173
00:07:40,860 --> 00:07:42,028
-You could?
-Yes.

174
00:07:42,094 --> 00:07:45,731
-Retirement Maker.
-Yes, Retirement Maker.

175
00:07:45,798 --> 00:07:51,604
Nam-il was very popular among women
during the 2002 World Cup,

176
00:07:51,671 --> 00:07:54,640
<i>and his popularity was such a syndrome</i>
<i>that it made the news.</i>

177
00:07:54,707 --> 00:07:56,075
<i>You were on the news a lot.</i>

178
00:07:56,142 --> 00:07:57,210
STUDYING HIS FACE

179
00:07:57,276 --> 00:08:00,112
-Can we discuss the year 2002?
-Why not?

180
00:08:00,179 --> 00:08:02,982
-I'm feeling conscious of him.
-Yes, right.

181
00:08:03,049 --> 00:08:04,951
-This is…
-In case you don't know,

182
00:08:05,017 --> 00:08:08,654
these two played in the 2002 World Cup,

183
00:08:08,721 --> 00:08:13,793
but Dong-gook sadly didn't make the cut.

184
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:15,261
-It's okay.
-Is it?

185
00:08:15,328 --> 00:08:17,163
-It's about Nam-il.
-Yes.

186
00:08:17,230 --> 00:08:21,033
It's been over 20 years,
so how long will you talk about 2002?

187
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:23,102
SLOWLY GETTING ANGRY

188
00:08:23,169 --> 00:08:24,370
From what I heard,

189
00:08:24,437 --> 00:08:28,274
you didn't watch
a single game of the 2002 World Cup.

190
00:08:28,341 --> 00:08:30,776
-Some even said that.
-I wouldn't want to watch it.

191
00:08:30,843 --> 00:08:33,713
Back then, I was still immature

192
00:08:33,779 --> 00:08:35,615
-and too soft-hearted.
-Right.

193
00:08:35,681 --> 00:08:38,584
About five or six of my friends thought

194
00:08:38,651 --> 00:08:42,755
we should all stay away
from watching the World Cup.

195
00:08:42,822 --> 00:08:45,191
We even went into a mountain
to avoid the games.

196
00:08:45,258 --> 00:08:46,559
To avoid the games?

197
00:08:46,626 --> 00:08:48,761
Because he could probably hear everything.

198
00:08:48,828 --> 00:08:50,830
He even heard it in the mountains.

199
00:08:50,897 --> 00:08:52,164
Because the monks were watching.

200
00:08:52,231 --> 00:08:53,232
EVEN MONKS WERE CHEERING

201
00:08:53,299 --> 00:08:56,769
-Even the monks watched.
-Yes, they'd all watch in their temples.

202
00:08:56,836 --> 00:09:01,474
When Dong-gook sadly didn't make the cut,
someone stayed and comforted him.

203
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:03,075
Really? That sounds like a great person.

204
00:09:03,142 --> 00:09:06,212
-It was Nam-il.
-I see.

205
00:09:06,279 --> 00:09:08,614
He was like,
"Come. Let's have a glass of soju."

206
00:09:08,681 --> 00:09:11,183
I still have
a lot of love and respect for Dong-gook,

207
00:09:11,250 --> 00:09:15,755
but back then,
I depended very much on him.

208
00:09:15,821 --> 00:09:18,157
But he was cut from the entry
on the last day,

209
00:09:18,224 --> 00:09:19,759
and it broke my heart.

210
00:09:19,825 --> 00:09:23,696
That was why I called him out for a drink.

211
00:09:23,763 --> 00:09:26,032
-I remember that.
-You do?

212
00:09:26,098 --> 00:09:29,435
Nam-il rarely ever enjoys a drink,

213
00:09:29,502 --> 00:09:31,437
but he invited me out for a drink first.

214
00:09:31,504 --> 00:09:32,505
So I went.

215
00:09:32,572 --> 00:09:34,340
He literally had one shot of soju.

216
00:09:35,875 --> 00:09:39,011
-He can't take his alcohol.
-He couldn't drink too much.

217
00:09:39,078 --> 00:09:42,014
That's a huge commitment
if his limit is one shot, and he had one.

218
00:09:42,081 --> 00:09:45,551
I was about to get started,

219
00:09:45,618 --> 00:09:46,953
but he went out and wailed.

220
00:09:47,019 --> 00:09:48,754
He's like, "What will Dong-gook do?"

221
00:09:48,821 --> 00:09:53,492
-I mean, he's the one who wants to cry.
-"Don't do this to Dong-gook!"

222
00:09:53,559 --> 00:09:54,927
"He should've made the cut."

223
00:09:54,994 --> 00:09:56,862
If he had one shot, he must've been drunk.

224
00:09:56,929 --> 00:09:59,098
He shed tears for me,

225
00:09:59,165 --> 00:10:01,300
-so I was very grateful for him.
-How sweet.

226
00:10:01,367 --> 00:10:02,835
My gosh. Okay.

227
00:10:03,402 --> 00:10:05,871
Then can we talk a bit more?

228
00:10:05,938 --> 00:10:08,107
Stop it. 2002 was ages ago.

229
00:10:08,174 --> 00:10:09,809
Please stop.

230
00:10:09,875 --> 00:10:12,044
-Everyone.
-Hey, he just asked you to stop.

231
00:10:12,111 --> 00:10:14,146
-Yes, right.
-Fabri is from Italy!

232
00:10:14,213 --> 00:10:15,581
I'll stop.

233
00:10:15,648 --> 00:10:19,952
I feel so uncomfortable
sitting between these two.

234
00:10:20,019 --> 00:10:21,220
Yes, right. Fabri was here.

235
00:10:21,287 --> 00:10:23,456
You were in Italy back then, right?

236
00:10:23,522 --> 00:10:25,358
I watched the game with my friend.

237
00:10:25,424 --> 00:10:28,461
The result broke our hearts,
but we had to accept it.

238
00:10:28,995 --> 00:10:30,062
All of you…

239
00:10:30,129 --> 00:10:31,564
Oh, no. I'm sorry.

240
00:10:33,199 --> 00:10:37,169
-That was a big blow.
-You can't say that!

241
00:10:37,236 --> 00:10:38,971
You didn't have to point it out.

242
00:10:39,038 --> 00:10:42,108
-Why did you have to hurt him?
-I'm sorry.

243
00:10:42,174 --> 00:10:44,410
But, yes, we accepted our defeat.

244
00:10:44,477 --> 00:10:45,945
-We did.
-You should give them that.

245
00:10:46,012 --> 00:10:47,146
Moreno, that punk…

246
00:10:47,213 --> 00:10:48,648
CLASPING HIS MOUTH

247
00:10:48,714 --> 00:10:51,751
-Moreno? Did you just swear?
-The referee.

248
00:10:51,817 --> 00:10:53,619
It wasn't a swear word.

249
00:10:53,686 --> 00:10:56,555
-We have no hard feelings.
-He's cool now.

250
00:10:56,622 --> 00:10:57,957
If you want to go back,

251
00:10:58,024 --> 00:10:59,925
I'll protect you.

252
00:11:00,693 --> 00:11:03,062
-A bodyguard.
-How will you do that?

253
00:11:03,129 --> 00:11:04,296
-Like this.
-Thank you.

254
00:11:04,363 --> 00:11:05,765
It's all in the past.

255
00:11:05,831 --> 00:11:07,767
You need to do your best
to hold your position here.

256
00:11:07,833 --> 00:11:09,769
HIS RIVAL FOR THE SAME POSITION

257
00:11:09,835 --> 00:11:10,936
You're right.

258
00:11:11,003 --> 00:11:15,708
And now, let's find out
what's in Nam-il's fridge.

259
00:11:15,775 --> 00:11:17,076
-Are you nervous?
-Right?

260
00:11:17,143 --> 00:11:19,278
-I have nothing to be nervous about.
-Right.

261
00:11:19,345 --> 00:11:20,913
Nam-il's fridge.

262
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:22,314
What is this?

263
00:11:22,381 --> 00:11:25,851
My wife, Bo-min,
bought that at a vintage store.

264
00:11:26,552 --> 00:11:30,623
But it looks kind of cooler here
compared to when it's sitting at home.

265
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:34,226
We'll go through
these ingredients in a bit.

266
00:11:34,293 --> 00:11:37,430
What does Nam-il have in his fridge?

267
00:11:37,496 --> 00:11:38,664
Let's take a look.

268
00:11:39,899 --> 00:11:41,867
-Whoa.
-Yes.

269
00:11:41,934 --> 00:11:42,935
Let's take a look.

270
00:11:43,002 --> 00:11:44,837
KIM NAM-IL'S FRIDGE

271
00:11:45,337 --> 00:11:47,373
-Yes.
-It's packed.

272
00:11:47,440 --> 00:11:49,875
-That's a lot.
-You can tell they cook at home.

273
00:11:49,942 --> 00:11:52,278
Let's look at the top shelf.

274
00:11:52,344 --> 00:11:55,381
I found this. Bolognese sauce.

275
00:11:55,448 --> 00:11:56,982
-Bolognese?
-Pasta sauce.

276
00:11:57,049 --> 00:11:59,318
My wife likes Western cuisine,

277
00:11:59,385 --> 00:12:02,521
-so she often makes pasta.
-You eat lots of pasta?

278
00:12:02,588 --> 00:12:05,491
-You also played abroad.
-Yes.

279
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:07,193
When you played in the Netherlands
and Russia,

280
00:12:07,259 --> 00:12:09,562
did you like the food there?

281
00:12:09,628 --> 00:12:11,464
I'm not a picky eater,

282
00:12:11,530 --> 00:12:14,233
so I didn't have
too many problems in those countries.

283
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:16,836
But I'd miss Korean food
from time to time.

284
00:12:16,902 --> 00:12:17,903
Yes, I can imagine.

285
00:12:17,970 --> 00:12:19,872
What did you do
when you craved Korean food?

286
00:12:19,939 --> 00:12:22,308
When I was in Russia,

287
00:12:22,374 --> 00:12:25,644
I bought beef bones
and made beef bone broth myself.

288
00:12:25,711 --> 00:12:27,046
-Whoa.
-Really?

289
00:12:27,113 --> 00:12:28,514
So you cooked.

290
00:12:28,581 --> 00:12:31,484
I'd make dishes
like kimchi <i>jjigae </i>and <i>ramyeon</i>.

291
00:12:31,550 --> 00:12:33,252
Do you like soup dishes?

292
00:12:33,319 --> 00:12:35,354
-Yes, I love soup dishes.
-I see.

293
00:12:35,421 --> 00:12:36,922
You can't have enough of soup.

294
00:12:36,989 --> 00:12:38,758
And over here.

295
00:12:38,824 --> 00:12:41,827
Is this salted seafood? Salted clams.

296
00:12:41,894 --> 00:12:44,430
-That's from Jung-hwan.
-It looks delicious.

297
00:12:44,497 --> 00:12:46,766
-Really?
-Jung-hwan gave it to you?

298
00:12:46,832 --> 00:12:50,402
Yes, he insisted that I take it home.

299
00:12:51,437 --> 00:12:54,774
I was scheduled to be on the show,

300
00:12:54,840 --> 00:12:57,777
so he probably wanted me to share it here.

301
00:12:57,843 --> 00:12:59,411
I gave it to you before that.

302
00:12:59,478 --> 00:13:00,713
You'd known I'd be here.

303
00:13:00,780 --> 00:13:03,215
You can't lie on TV.

304
00:13:03,282 --> 00:13:05,084
Do you like salted clams?

305
00:13:05,151 --> 00:13:07,219
It's not my staple.

306
00:13:07,286 --> 00:13:08,854
It's just that he gave it to me.

307
00:13:08,921 --> 00:13:10,823
Then you should've turned it down.

308
00:13:10,890 --> 00:13:12,057
You told me to take it!

309
00:13:12,124 --> 00:13:13,392
I gave it because it was good!

310
00:13:13,459 --> 00:13:16,595
You talk just like Jung-hwan.

311
00:13:16,662 --> 00:13:21,066
Dong-gook, have you
ever received anything from Jung-hwan?

312
00:13:21,133 --> 00:13:23,002
He only threw swear words at me.

313
00:13:23,068 --> 00:13:24,870
Only swear words.

314
00:13:24,937 --> 00:13:26,939
-You should be relieved.
-At least it was just words.

315
00:13:27,006 --> 00:13:30,042
-But it was good.
-Was it? Okay.

316
00:13:30,109 --> 00:13:31,377
The second shelf.

317
00:13:31,443 --> 00:13:35,681
-I see kimchi on this shelf.
-He has lots of them.

318
00:13:35,748 --> 00:13:38,918
-"Kimchi and radish from Namhae."
-Yes.

319
00:13:38,984 --> 00:13:41,453
This is "Kwak's kimchi."

320
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:44,857
"Radish from Namhae,
radish kimchi from <i>gomtang </i>place."

321
00:13:44,924 --> 00:13:47,493
<i>-I knew you liked kimchi, but this much?</i>
<i>-Really.</i>

322
00:13:47,560 --> 00:13:49,328
"Eat this after April 1st."

323
00:13:49,395 --> 00:13:52,298
"Mature in shade.
Remove ginger before eating."

324
00:13:52,364 --> 00:13:54,767
-How meticulous.
-First off,

325
00:13:54,834 --> 00:13:58,470
I can't have a meal without kimchi.
I love it that much.

326
00:13:58,537 --> 00:14:00,673
I have three different people
who send me kimchi.

327
00:14:00,739 --> 00:14:02,308
Kwak is one of my students,

328
00:14:02,374 --> 00:14:05,578
and his mother
runs a restaurant in Jeonju.

329
00:14:05,644 --> 00:14:07,580
Who made this? Where did you get this?

330
00:14:07,646 --> 00:14:10,015
-That's from my sister-in-law.
-Your sister-in-law.

331
00:14:10,082 --> 00:14:13,052
I said I was craving water kimchi,

332
00:14:13,118 --> 00:14:14,320
and she offered to make it.

333
00:14:14,386 --> 00:14:16,989
She did it for her brother-in-law.

334
00:14:17,056 --> 00:14:20,426
But I'm not so good with spicy food now.

335
00:14:20,492 --> 00:14:22,161
Is kimchi <i>jjigae</i> all right, though?

336
00:14:22,228 --> 00:14:23,863
-That's fine.
-I see.

337
00:14:23,929 --> 00:14:26,098
Hey, look at this.

338
00:14:26,165 --> 00:14:28,300
I found trees. What are these?

339
00:14:28,367 --> 00:14:30,669
-It's covered in dirt.
-What are those?

340
00:14:30,736 --> 00:14:32,404
-Chinese yams.
-Are these Chinese yams?

341
00:14:32,471 --> 00:14:37,543
I love to put ground Chinese yams on rice
with soy sauce.

342
00:14:37,610 --> 00:14:39,411
HE LOVES SOY SAUCE,
CHINESE YAM, AND RICE

343
00:14:39,478 --> 00:14:41,480
It's seafood over here.

344
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:45,084
-Cutlassfish. There are four pieces.
-Those look fresh.

345
00:14:45,150 --> 00:14:47,052
These are half-dried fish.

346
00:14:47,119 --> 00:14:48,587
It's redfish.

347
00:14:48,654 --> 00:14:50,189
Atka mackerel.

348
00:14:50,256 --> 00:14:51,457
Brown croaker.

349
00:14:51,523 --> 00:14:54,693
-He has brown croakers.
-He even has brown croakers?

350
00:14:54,760 --> 00:14:56,962
You see, I'm from an island.

351
00:14:57,029 --> 00:14:59,732
So I grew up eating lots of fish.

352
00:14:59,798 --> 00:15:01,567
-That's true.
-He's from an island.

353
00:15:01,634 --> 00:15:05,037
There are many different kinds of fish,
so you can feel free to pick and choose.

354
00:15:05,104 --> 00:15:08,474
Whoa, hey. I found something nice.

355
00:15:08,540 --> 00:15:10,242
It says what it is.

356
00:15:10,309 --> 00:15:12,912
-Oxtail, April 2025.
-Oxtail.

357
00:15:12,978 --> 00:15:16,415
"Power." It says power.

358
00:15:16,482 --> 00:15:19,218
-What is that?
-Why did you write down "power"?

359
00:15:19,285 --> 00:15:23,856
I've been low on energy recently,
so she probably wanted to rejuvenate me.

360
00:15:23,923 --> 00:15:26,926
-And now, room temperature ingredients.
-It's like a convenience store.

361
00:15:26,992 --> 00:15:29,595
-Yes, there are lots of things.
-You keep that at home?

362
00:15:29,662 --> 00:15:31,597
I'm seeing lots of noodles.

363
00:15:31,664 --> 00:15:32,665
Do you enjoy noodles?

364
00:15:32,731 --> 00:15:35,401
Udon, soba, <i>kalguksu</i>, <i>naengmyeon</i>…

365
00:15:35,467 --> 00:15:37,903
I love all noodle dishes.

366
00:15:37,970 --> 00:15:39,171
Does he have pasta?

367
00:15:39,238 --> 00:15:41,073
Fabri asks if he has pasta.

368
00:15:41,140 --> 00:15:42,775
-Does he have pasta?
-Pasta?

369
00:15:42,841 --> 00:15:44,143
Thin noodles.

370
00:15:44,209 --> 00:15:45,711
These are gardenia noodles.

371
00:15:45,778 --> 00:15:47,846
-Gardenia noodles.
-Gardenia noodles.

372
00:15:47,913 --> 00:15:49,481
Something written in Japanese.

373
00:15:49,548 --> 00:15:50,916
Those are buckwheat noodles.

374
00:15:50,983 --> 00:15:54,086
-He doesn't have pasta.
-He doesn't.

375
00:15:54,153 --> 00:15:57,022
-There are sauces too.
-He has lots of things.

376
00:15:57,089 --> 00:15:59,692
There are lots of ingredients,
so please choose carefully.

377
00:15:59,758 --> 00:16:01,860
That was Nam-il's fridge!

378
00:16:01,927 --> 00:16:04,730
DONE INVESTIGATING HIS FRIDGE!

379
00:16:04,797 --> 00:16:08,033
We'll find out Nam-il's orders

380
00:16:08,100 --> 00:16:10,602
and figure out the contenders.

381
00:16:10,669 --> 00:16:12,371
Show us his orders.

382
00:16:12,938 --> 00:16:14,306
What's the first order?

383
00:16:14,373 --> 00:16:16,842
"Soup will come true."

384
00:16:16,909 --> 00:16:21,447
So I want to eat a soup dish
that I've never had before in my life.

385
00:16:21,513 --> 00:16:23,515
Nothing ordinary will cut it.

386
00:16:23,582 --> 00:16:25,184
What's his next order?

387
00:16:27,019 --> 00:16:30,589
"Again 2002, recharge the vacuum cleaner."

388
00:16:30,656 --> 00:16:32,891
I started losing energy little by little
since then.

389
00:16:32,958 --> 00:16:35,194
So I wanted to eat a healthy dish

390
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:39,431
-A healthy dish.
-That'll replenish my energy.

391
00:16:39,498 --> 00:16:42,201
<i>-He wants to get back his hot temper.</i>
<i>-Right?</i>

392
00:16:42,267 --> 00:16:43,569
-I remember.
-That energetic guy.

393
00:16:43,635 --> 00:16:46,872
-Something that'll give me a dopamine hit.
-Do you want a dopamine hit?

394
00:16:46,939 --> 00:16:50,609
As soon as I heard this,
I knew I had to cook for him.

395
00:16:50,676 --> 00:16:53,412
I want to see his temper once again.

396
00:16:53,479 --> 00:16:55,881
I want to give him that dopamine hit.

397
00:16:55,948 --> 00:16:57,549
I hope he gets replenished.

398
00:16:57,616 --> 00:17:00,452
I want to get my revenge.

399
00:17:00,519 --> 00:17:01,920
-For 2002?
-Yes.

400
00:17:01,987 --> 00:17:05,190
Poong and Fabri are
in the Korea-Italy rematch.

401
00:17:05,257 --> 00:17:08,994
Next, "soup will come true."
Soup dish.

402
00:17:09,061 --> 00:17:10,362
I should do it.

403
00:17:10,429 --> 00:17:12,564
I'll make that soup come true.

404
00:17:13,532 --> 00:17:14,600
Who else?

405
00:17:14,666 --> 00:17:16,935
-I'll make soup.
-Hey.

406
00:17:17,002 --> 00:17:18,670
Hyun-suk versus Eun-yeong.

407
00:17:18,737 --> 00:17:22,341
Representing Italy, Fabri is
up against Poong, representing Korea.

408
00:17:22,408 --> 00:17:23,809
Let us begin.

409
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:26,211
THE COOK-OFF BEGINS

410
00:17:26,278 --> 00:17:30,315
The first round with Nam-il's ingredients.

411
00:17:30,382 --> 00:17:32,918
The dark horse of <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>
Chef Eun-yeong, is

412
00:17:32,985 --> 00:17:37,856
up against the winning chef,
Chef Hyun-suk, for the first time.

413
00:17:37,923 --> 00:17:41,493
This order is titled,
"Soup will come true."

414
00:17:41,560 --> 00:17:43,762
Do you see that star
next to the word "soup"?

415
00:17:43,829 --> 00:17:48,400
You get to wear a star on your uniform
when you win the World Cup.

416
00:17:48,467 --> 00:17:52,104
Here on this show,
we also give a star with every victory.

417
00:17:52,171 --> 00:17:53,906
Chef Hyun-suk has won six times.

418
00:17:53,972 --> 00:17:56,241
He's the first place among all chefs.

419
00:17:56,308 --> 00:17:59,044
-Eun-yeong has three wins and one loss.
-Three wins, one loss.

420
00:17:59,111 --> 00:18:01,113
She won three times

421
00:18:01,180 --> 00:18:04,450
against Poong, Ho-young, and Yeon-bok.

422
00:18:04,516 --> 00:18:05,851
Whoa, really?

423
00:18:05,918 --> 00:18:10,222
She won against
every single returning chefs.

424
00:18:10,289 --> 00:18:11,857
She must be talented.

425
00:18:11,924 --> 00:18:16,361
As a kid who grew up with this show,
I cultivated my dream as I watched him.

426
00:18:16,428 --> 00:18:18,897
He's one of the key people
among the returning chefs.

427
00:18:18,964 --> 00:18:20,399
-He is.
-Yes.

428
00:18:20,466 --> 00:18:25,270
I must defeat the best chef among
returning chefs to establish myself here.

429
00:18:25,337 --> 00:18:27,072
I need to win against this final boss.

430
00:18:27,139 --> 00:18:29,908
-Chef Gyeong-jun won the previous round.
-Yes.

431
00:18:29,975 --> 00:18:33,045
If he loses again, there will be
a generational transition of the chefs.

432
00:18:33,112 --> 00:18:38,417
I see. It must be about time he retired.

433
00:18:38,484 --> 00:18:41,954
The discipline in the world of chefs
had fallen apart ages ago.

434
00:18:42,721 --> 00:18:45,991
Chef Hyun-suk
always puts on a good performance, right?

435
00:18:46,058 --> 00:18:50,062
So I prepared a wok today, a Chinese wok.

436
00:18:50,129 --> 00:18:52,397
-She'll perform better.
-I'll try to seize your attention.

437
00:18:52,464 --> 00:18:54,566
She also said she'd put on a performance,

438
00:18:54,633 --> 00:18:57,369
so I guess this might be
a challenge for me.

439
00:18:57,436 --> 00:18:59,671
Are you challenging yourself again?

440
00:18:59,738 --> 00:19:03,475
I'm suffering
from a very serious back injury.

441
00:19:03,542 --> 00:19:05,077
It's hard for me to stand

442
00:19:05,144 --> 00:19:07,713
for more than five minutes,

443
00:19:07,779 --> 00:19:10,949
but I'll bite the bullet
and cook for Nam-il.

444
00:19:11,016 --> 00:19:12,818
-It's a challenge against myself.
-Sure.

445
00:19:12,885 --> 00:19:14,586
I'm moved.

446
00:19:14,653 --> 00:19:15,854
He has a bad back right now,

447
00:19:15,921 --> 00:19:18,023
and it's because he recently played golf.

448
00:19:18,090 --> 00:19:21,160
-It was from golf?
-He got it from playing golf?

449
00:19:21,226 --> 00:19:23,529
He wasn't injured at work.
He got hurt playing golf.

450
00:19:23,595 --> 00:19:25,564
I was on a business trip.

451
00:19:25,631 --> 00:19:29,735
Anyway, it's between a young Chinese chef
and an old Western cuisine chef.

452
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:31,336
I look forward to this.

453
00:19:31,403 --> 00:19:32,738
"Old Western cuisine chef"?

454
00:19:32,804 --> 00:19:35,607
-He looks shaken up to be called old.
-He looks shaken up.

455
00:19:35,674 --> 00:19:37,242
Is it okay to be called
an old Western cuisine chef?

456
00:19:37,309 --> 00:19:41,914
My back, please hang in there
so that I can make a good dish for Nam-il.

457
00:19:41,980 --> 00:19:44,516
-I see.
-If his back pain is that bad…

458
00:19:44,583 --> 00:19:45,784
He's playing with an injury.

459
00:19:46,618 --> 00:19:48,887
CHEF EUN-YEONG'S INGREDIENTS: TOFU,
OYAKODON SAUCE POWDER, SLICED JALAPEÑO

460
00:19:48,954 --> 00:19:51,123
HALF-DRIED REDFISH, WATER KIMCHI, KIMCHI,
HALF-DRIED BROWN CROAKER, BEAN SPROUTS

461
00:19:51,190 --> 00:19:52,758
The dish I prepared is called

462
00:19:52,824 --> 00:19:54,593
White Out Soup.

463
00:19:54,660 --> 00:19:57,229
-White Out Soup.
-White Out Soup.

464
00:19:57,296 --> 00:19:58,730
White Out Soup.

465
00:19:58,797 --> 00:20:01,600
I'll use fish bones
to make milky-white soup.

466
00:20:01,667 --> 00:20:03,368
That's really delicious.

467
00:20:03,435 --> 00:20:05,971
I'll use redfish and brown croaker.

468
00:20:06,038 --> 00:20:08,307
I'll use the fish meat
to make dumplings without skin,

469
00:20:08,373 --> 00:20:11,743
and use the bones to make milky broth
to make a refreshing and spicy soup.

470
00:20:11,810 --> 00:20:13,812
-That's the soup--
-Excuse me, I'm sorry.

471
00:20:13,879 --> 00:20:16,348
Can I use all of my back power

472
00:20:16,415 --> 00:20:20,118
to cook for Nam-il later?
Let me lean on the counter right now.

473
00:20:20,185 --> 00:20:22,487
-He's cooking with an injury.
-He's cooking with an injury.

474
00:20:22,554 --> 00:20:24,590
-I see.
-So did you hit a birdie?

475
00:20:25,424 --> 00:20:26,825
I did.

476
00:20:26,892 --> 00:20:30,729
He did a birdie,
but he can't stand straight anymore.

477
00:20:30,796 --> 00:20:33,498
You were too into the game.

478
00:20:33,565 --> 00:20:35,734
Anyway, you can lean on the counter.
You're injured anyway.

479
00:20:35,801 --> 00:20:36,935
He wasn't hurt while cooking.

480
00:20:37,002 --> 00:20:39,204
We're sorry that we cut you off.

481
00:20:39,271 --> 00:20:40,472
I'm sorry.

482
00:20:40,539 --> 00:20:42,074
-Will you please continue?
-Yes.

483
00:20:42,140 --> 00:20:44,476
Well, I'm done.

484
00:20:44,543 --> 00:20:45,644
She's done.

485
00:20:46,311 --> 00:20:48,847
You took her time on air
with your back pain.

486
00:20:48,914 --> 00:20:50,382
It's awkward now.

487
00:20:50,449 --> 00:20:52,351
We forgot what she said.

488
00:20:52,417 --> 00:20:56,355
But can you make fish bone broth
in only 15 minutes?

489
00:20:56,421 --> 00:21:00,359
I have a secret to making
quick milky-white fish bone broth.

490
00:21:00,425 --> 00:21:01,793
I'll show you later.

491
00:21:01,860 --> 00:21:03,629
-In 15 minutes.
-But it'll be milky-white, right?

492
00:21:03,695 --> 00:21:05,697
-Yes, it'll be milky and white.
-Milky.

493
00:21:06,632 --> 00:21:08,800
CHEF HYUN-SUK'S INGREDIENTS:
PINEAPPLE FLAVOR SODA, RADISH, SEAWEED

494
00:21:08,867 --> 00:21:11,036
DRIED HERRING, BONE BROTH, SALTED SHRIMP,
DRIED SHRIMP, TSUYU, CUTLASSFISH

495
00:21:11,937 --> 00:21:13,839
He's suffering with back pain.

496
00:21:13,905 --> 00:21:16,308
-We have to ban him from doing this.
-He's injured.

497
00:21:16,375 --> 00:21:17,709
Chef Hyun-suk is competing

498
00:21:17,776 --> 00:21:19,745
despite his painful injury.

499
00:21:19,811 --> 00:21:20,979
What are you making?

500
00:21:21,046 --> 00:21:22,214
My dish is called

501
00:21:22,281 --> 00:21:24,383
National Seaweed Soup.

502
00:21:24,449 --> 00:21:26,952
-What? National Seaweed Soup?
-National Seaweed Soup?

503
00:21:27,019 --> 00:21:29,121
I'm going to make the dish

504
00:21:29,187 --> 00:21:31,790
<i>I made on </i>Culinary Class Wars
<i>during the team round.</i>

505
00:21:31,857 --> 00:21:33,625
He's grinding seaweed.

506
00:21:33,692 --> 00:21:35,560
<i>I said it was seaweed soup,</i>

507
00:21:35,627 --> 00:21:39,398
<i>but it's more like a fish dish</i>
<i>you'll eat in a Western course meal.</i>

508
00:21:39,464 --> 00:21:44,670
Poong once got inspired by that
and made a downgraded version of it.

509
00:21:45,237 --> 00:21:47,439
So it was fishy and all.

510
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:51,576
But I'll make
the ultimate version of that soup.

511
00:21:51,643 --> 00:21:54,146
Have you ever had
seaweed soup with cutlassfish?

512
00:21:54,212 --> 00:21:55,781
-What?
-Seaweed soup with cutlassfish?

513
00:21:55,847 --> 00:21:57,883
-I've had it in Jeju.
-Yes, right.

514
00:21:57,949 --> 00:22:00,285
It may seem familiar,
but everyone said the same thing.

515
00:22:01,687 --> 00:22:03,188
My dishes are different.

516
00:22:03,255 --> 00:22:06,058
It's different when Hyun-suk makes it.

517
00:22:06,124 --> 00:22:11,430
Let's begin the round titled
"Soup will come true" for Nam-il.

518
00:22:11,496 --> 00:22:12,931
Whoa.

519
00:22:12,998 --> 00:22:15,834
She wants to rise above as the best chef

520
00:22:15,901 --> 00:22:18,303
by surpassing Chef Hyun-suk today.

521
00:22:18,370 --> 00:22:20,939
The young blood of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,
Chef Park Eun-yeong.

522
00:22:21,006 --> 00:22:24,276
This man wants to do anything
to bring discipline to the world of chefs.

523
00:22:24,343 --> 00:22:28,313
Kim Nam-il of <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>
Chef Choi Hyun-suk is up against her.

524
00:22:28,380 --> 00:22:30,916
Will there be a generational transition?
Or will he teach her a lesson?

525
00:22:30,982 --> 00:22:34,252
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

526
00:22:36,488 --> 00:22:39,825
-Has it begun?
-Yes, it has. They get just 15 minutes.

527
00:22:39,891 --> 00:22:42,494
How will they make
that deep flavor in just 15 minutes?

528
00:22:42,561 --> 00:22:44,329
Yes, they're making soup.

529
00:22:44,396 --> 00:22:47,232
It takes a long time
to make fish bone broth.

530
00:22:47,299 --> 00:22:48,834
What's that fish?

531
00:22:48,900 --> 00:22:51,002
-It's redfish.
-Redfish.

532
00:22:51,069 --> 00:22:53,271
-Has it been dried?
-Yes, half-dried.

533
00:22:53,338 --> 00:22:54,339
I see.

534
00:22:54,406 --> 00:22:56,441
SHE CAN MULTITASK, COOKING AND
ANSWERING AT THE SAME TIME

535
00:22:57,008 --> 00:23:00,779
PREPARING THE REDFISH

536
00:23:02,714 --> 00:23:04,149
DONE IN A FLASH

537
00:23:04,716 --> 00:23:06,151
NEXT FISH, BROWN CROAKER

538
00:23:07,152 --> 00:23:09,154
My gosh. Already?

539
00:23:09,888 --> 00:23:12,190
SHE GRABS
JUST THE FISH HEADS AND BONES

540
00:23:13,725 --> 00:23:14,893
AND THROWS THEM INTO OIL

541
00:23:14,960 --> 00:23:17,763
She's moving very fast. Already?

542
00:23:17,829 --> 00:23:18,897
She's frying the fish.

543
00:23:18,964 --> 00:23:20,999
She's frying the fish
instead of boiling it.

544
00:23:21,066 --> 00:23:22,234
Whoa, the green onion.

545
00:23:22,300 --> 00:23:24,002
Did she put in a whole green onion?

546
00:23:24,069 --> 00:23:28,673
The broth may taste too fishy
if you make it with half-dried seafood.

547
00:23:28,740 --> 00:23:29,908
But if you fry it,

548
00:23:29,975 --> 00:23:31,710
that fishy smell will disappear.

549
00:23:31,777 --> 00:23:34,679
The fishy smell disappears,
and it brings out its taste.

550
00:23:34,746 --> 00:23:36,181
I didn't know about that method.

551
00:23:36,248 --> 00:23:38,884
SHE STORES THE STEAMER TOP
IN THE SINK

552
00:23:39,451 --> 00:23:41,052
HYUN-SUK BEGINS
BY CHOPPING RADISH

553
00:23:41,119 --> 00:23:43,388
IT LOOKS COMPLETELY RECTANGULAR

554
00:23:44,289 --> 00:23:47,426
-What's that?
-Radish and soy sauce?

555
00:23:47,492 --> 00:23:49,594
He must be making braised radish.

556
00:23:49,661 --> 00:23:50,962
He's using hot water.

557
00:23:51,029 --> 00:23:53,331
-It's not just water. Was it soy sauce…
-It's <i>tsuyu</i>.

558
00:23:53,398 --> 00:23:54,399
Is that <i>tsuyu</i>?

559
00:23:54,466 --> 00:23:56,401
I'm braising it in <i>tsuyu</i>.

560
00:23:56,468 --> 00:23:58,670
-I see.
-With a microwave?

561
00:23:58,737 --> 00:24:01,039
It's the fastest method of cooking.

562
00:24:01,106 --> 00:24:03,909
He'll microwave that and cook it.

563
00:24:03,975 --> 00:24:06,645
Yes, he'll have to do that
if he only has 15 minutes.

564
00:24:06,711 --> 00:24:08,480
What are you heating up, Chef Hyun-suk?

565
00:24:08,547 --> 00:24:10,749
-It's beef bone broth.
-Beef bone broth.

566
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:11,817
The frozen broth?

567
00:24:11,883 --> 00:24:13,051
What's that?

568
00:24:13,118 --> 00:24:15,787
He had salted shrimp sauce,

569
00:24:15,854 --> 00:24:17,789
so I put it in to add some umami.

570
00:24:17,856 --> 00:24:20,325
He's making the most
out of the available ingredients.

571
00:24:21,827 --> 00:24:23,929
The fried fish.

572
00:24:24,496 --> 00:24:26,264
SMASHING

573
00:24:26,331 --> 00:24:30,802
She's smashing the fried fish bones.

574
00:24:32,204 --> 00:24:33,705
Is she using that for her dish?

575
00:24:33,772 --> 00:24:35,340
-The broth.
-I'll make broth with it.

576
00:24:35,407 --> 00:24:37,175
She's using that to make broth?

577
00:24:37,242 --> 00:24:40,345
But Chef Hyun-suk is using
the bone broth he already had.

578
00:24:40,412 --> 00:24:42,614
Chef Eun-yeong is
making the broth herself.

579
00:24:42,681 --> 00:24:44,182
I'm serious about this.

580
00:24:44,249 --> 00:24:46,251
Doesn't this show
different levels of effort?

581
00:24:46,318 --> 00:24:48,787
-The level of dedication's different.
-Right?

582
00:24:48,854 --> 00:24:49,855
Yes.

583
00:24:49,921 --> 00:24:51,356
THE RETURNING CHEF KILLER
GETS AHEAD IN EFFORT

584
00:24:52,357 --> 00:24:55,560
Chef Hyun-suk is preparing cutlassfish.

585
00:24:55,627 --> 00:24:57,929
-Are you putting that into the soup?
-Yes.

586
00:24:57,996 --> 00:24:58,997
HE CUTS OUT JUST THE FLESH

587
00:24:59,564 --> 00:25:01,833
EVEN THE CUTLASSFISH
IS RECTANGULAR

588
00:25:02,400 --> 00:25:04,135
PUTS FLOUR INTO A BOWL

589
00:25:05,737 --> 00:25:07,906
Why are you adding soda there?

590
00:25:07,973 --> 00:25:11,209
I have to let this sit
to add layers of air into the fry batter.

591
00:25:11,276 --> 00:25:12,711
But I have no time to wait,

592
00:25:12,777 --> 00:25:15,680
so I want to make it crunchier
by using soda.

593
00:25:15,747 --> 00:25:19,084
-People often use beer.
-Yes, he's supposed to use beer.

594
00:25:19,150 --> 00:25:20,418
Isn't that pineapple flavored?

595
00:25:20,485 --> 00:25:21,820
Yes, I like it.

596
00:25:21,887 --> 00:25:23,889
-I see.
-It was actual soda.

597
00:25:23,955 --> 00:25:26,992
It's his favorite pineapple-flavored soda.

598
00:25:27,058 --> 00:25:29,694
-Cutlassfish.
-He's going to fry the cutlassfish.

599
00:25:29,761 --> 00:25:33,465
Is he… He's frying the cutlassfish
before putting it in the soup.

600
00:25:33,532 --> 00:25:36,768
I think he'll top it on top of the soup.

601
00:25:36,835 --> 00:25:38,103
Gosh.

602
00:25:38,169 --> 00:25:42,207
He shows that his back is in pain
in the midst of everything.

603
00:25:42,274 --> 00:25:44,342
Stop acting.

604
00:25:45,210 --> 00:25:46,745
I need to let Nam-il eat good food.

605
00:25:46,811 --> 00:25:48,413
My back, hang in there.

606
00:25:49,347 --> 00:25:50,815
Do you like seeing crybabies?

607
00:25:51,583 --> 00:25:53,418
-I hate it the most.
-He hates crybabies.

608
00:25:53,485 --> 00:25:57,556
Soccer players hate it
when they see players lying on the pitch.

609
00:25:57,622 --> 00:26:00,759
Most players don't let opponents find out
about their injuries.

610
00:26:00,825 --> 00:26:03,728
-You're right.
-But he exposed himself from the start.

611
00:26:03,795 --> 00:26:06,231
It's like soccer players
faking their injury on the pitch.

612
00:26:06,298 --> 00:26:07,299
FAKING-COOKING

613
00:26:07,365 --> 00:26:08,466
-Faking on the pitch?
-Faking?

614
00:26:09,034 --> 00:26:11,202
THE REDFISH SHE PREPARED
WHEN MAKING THE BROTH

615
00:26:11,770 --> 00:26:14,005
1. CUT SKINNED REDFISH MEAT
AND GRIND IN AN IMMERSION BLENDER

616
00:26:14,072 --> 00:26:16,207
I think Chef Eun-yeong is
grinding fish meat.

617
00:26:16,274 --> 00:26:17,709
I'm making dumplings without skin.

618
00:26:17,776 --> 00:26:20,045
-I see.
-She said she'd make dumplings.

619
00:26:20,111 --> 00:26:21,680
And the fish meat is for the dumpling.

620
00:26:21,746 --> 00:26:23,782
Eun-yeong, is that kimchi?

621
00:26:23,848 --> 00:26:26,084
Yes, Nam-il said he liked kimchi,

622
00:26:26,151 --> 00:26:27,218
-so I'm using it.
-Which one is it?

623
00:26:27,285 --> 00:26:29,621
-The one from Namhae.
-Kimchi from Namhae.

624
00:26:30,188 --> 00:26:31,456
2. MAKING THE FILLING
WITH TOFU, REDFISH,

625
00:26:31,523 --> 00:26:32,557
KIMCHI, GINGER JUICE,
SALT, PEPPER

626
00:26:32,624 --> 00:26:33,658
Will you fry that too?

627
00:26:33,725 --> 00:26:36,461
-I'll steam it to make a clean taste.
-You'll steam it?

628
00:26:36,528 --> 00:26:38,129
-She's making dumplings without skin.
-Dumplings without skin.

629
00:26:38,196 --> 00:26:39,397
Dumplings without skin.

630
00:26:39,464 --> 00:26:40,899
-She'll just coat it with starch.
-Kimchi dumplings.

631
00:26:40,966 --> 00:26:41,967
It looks good.

632
00:26:42,534 --> 00:26:45,136
HE BEGINS TO MAKE SEAWEED SOUP

633
00:26:45,203 --> 00:26:46,204
Sesame oil.

634
00:26:46,271 --> 00:26:48,340
-He's…
-You're stir-frying the seaweed.

635
00:26:48,406 --> 00:26:49,407
Yes.

636
00:26:49,975 --> 00:26:52,544
CHECKING THE FRIED CUTLASSFISH

637
00:26:53,144 --> 00:26:55,747
HE PULLS IT OUT OF THE OIL

638
00:26:56,881 --> 00:26:59,084
AND COVERS IT
IN ANOTHER LAYER OF BATTER

639
00:26:59,150 --> 00:27:00,585
Are you frying it twice?

640
00:27:00,652 --> 00:27:03,021
I applied two layers of batter.

641
00:27:03,088 --> 00:27:05,857
-It's like fish and chips.
-Yes, it is.

642
00:27:05,924 --> 00:27:07,993
He wanted something new,

643
00:27:08,059 --> 00:27:11,730
so I'm making perfect balance
even with its texture.

644
00:27:11,796 --> 00:27:13,331
Chef Hyun-suk's back may hurt,

645
00:27:13,398 --> 00:27:17,235
-but his mouth must not hurt.
-Hey!

646
00:27:17,302 --> 00:27:21,406
-She just dissed you!
-Chef Eun-yeong!

647
00:27:21,473 --> 00:27:24,142
-He looks shaken up.
-Yes.

648
00:27:24,209 --> 00:27:26,311
-That was awful.
-I knew it.

649
00:27:26,378 --> 00:27:27,545
I keep my thing going.

650
00:27:27,612 --> 00:27:29,814
If his back hurts, he should be quiet too.

651
00:27:29,881 --> 00:27:32,550
-Yes, if it hurts, he can't talk.
-The old chef talks too much.

652
00:27:32,617 --> 00:27:34,886
My gosh. She's tougher than me.

653
00:27:34,953 --> 00:27:36,354
-She's saying he's faking it.
-Yes.

654
00:27:36,421 --> 00:27:38,256
IT'S FUN TO SEE IT IN PERSON

655
00:27:38,323 --> 00:27:40,358
She's the returning chef killer.

656
00:27:40,425 --> 00:27:42,627
-Don't be deceived, Nam-il.
-This is bad.

657
00:27:42,694 --> 00:27:43,895
The world of chefs

658
00:27:43,962 --> 00:27:45,730
have perished for good.

659
00:27:46,297 --> 00:27:47,565
THERE'S NO HIERARCHY

660
00:27:47,632 --> 00:27:49,567
THE OLD(?) WESTERN CUISINE CHEF
POURS THE BROTH

661
00:27:49,634 --> 00:27:51,436
He's boiling seaweed soup right now.

662
00:27:51,503 --> 00:27:54,239
And dumplings without skin.
Are you making just three?

663
00:27:54,305 --> 00:27:56,574
Wait, it looks like something is burning.

664
00:27:56,641 --> 00:27:58,209
-Is that burning?
-What is?

665
00:27:58,276 --> 00:27:59,544
-There's no water, right?
-There is none.

666
00:27:59,611 --> 00:28:01,780
-Pour water into it.
-What's going on?

667
00:28:01,846 --> 00:28:04,315
-What?
-No, this is bad!

668
00:28:04,382 --> 00:28:07,619
-No!
-I can smell something burning.

669
00:28:07,686 --> 00:28:10,288
-It's turning darker.
-She's smoking those instead of steaming.

670
00:28:10,355 --> 00:28:11,356
My goodness.

671
00:28:11,923 --> 00:28:13,925
PULLS THE FISH OUT
AND ASSESSES THE SITUATION

672
00:28:13,992 --> 00:28:16,127
It smells burnt.

673
00:28:16,194 --> 00:28:18,163
The water's all evaporated.

674
00:28:18,229 --> 00:28:20,298
Chef Hyun-suk,
why didn't you keep an eye out?

675
00:28:20,365 --> 00:28:21,466
What?

676
00:28:22,133 --> 00:28:24,803
"Why didn't you keep an eye out?"

677
00:28:25,370 --> 00:28:26,805
THE DISCIPLINE IS ALL-TIME LOW

678
00:28:26,871 --> 00:28:28,873
I have a lot on my plate as is.

679
00:28:28,940 --> 00:28:30,575
Where's the lid?

680
00:28:31,142 --> 00:28:33,044
SHE PUT IT IN THE SINK
AS SOON AS SHE BEGAN

681
00:28:33,111 --> 00:28:35,814
Didn't you just complain
against Chef Hyun-suk?

682
00:28:35,880 --> 00:28:37,048
SHE'S SHAKEN UP FOR THE 2ND TIME

683
00:28:37,115 --> 00:28:38,783
SUDDENLY INVADING HIS SIDE

684
00:28:38,850 --> 00:28:41,753
-Is there anything I can use?
-Why are you going there, Eun-yeong?

685
00:28:41,820 --> 00:28:45,123
-The lid is gone.
-Are you taking a walk?

686
00:28:45,190 --> 00:28:46,891
She has to steam it,
but she can't find the lid.

687
00:28:46,958 --> 00:28:48,693
-She can't find the lid to steam it?
-There's no lid.

688
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:49,961
Just use a frying pan.

689
00:28:50,028 --> 00:28:52,397
-Find it for her.
-Use a frying pan.

690
00:28:52,464 --> 00:28:54,566
She has to steam it,
but she can't find the lid.

691
00:28:54,632 --> 00:28:57,135
-She has to steam it, but…
-Fabri.

692
00:28:57,202 --> 00:28:59,270
-How nice. You got it.
-Thank you.

693
00:28:59,337 --> 00:29:00,538
SHE'S USING A FRYING PAN AS A LID

694
00:29:00,605 --> 00:29:04,042
She had to steam it. She seems flustered.

695
00:29:04,109 --> 00:29:05,744
Goodness, the time.

696
00:29:05,810 --> 00:29:08,947
She's adding some jalapeños.

697
00:29:09,013 --> 00:29:11,249
-Seven minutes.
-You have seven minutes.

698
00:29:11,316 --> 00:29:13,952
Seven minutes? Already?

699
00:29:14,018 --> 00:29:16,321
Time really flies. Gosh.

700
00:29:20,291 --> 00:29:22,293
Are you blending the seaweed soup?

701
00:29:22,360 --> 00:29:23,895
-I see.
-What?

702
00:29:23,962 --> 00:29:25,797
-Are you blending the soup?
-Really?

703
00:29:25,864 --> 00:29:27,232
It's like Western style soup.

704
00:29:27,298 --> 00:29:30,935
-Why is he blending it?
-He's blending the soup.

705
00:29:31,002 --> 00:29:32,771
It'll add a deeper flavor.

706
00:29:34,405 --> 00:29:36,775
ADDING TSUYU

707
00:29:37,342 --> 00:29:39,210
HE DOESN'T FORGET TO PERFORM

708
00:29:39,778 --> 00:29:42,480
EUN-YEONG GETS READY
TO PERFORM TOO

709
00:29:43,348 --> 00:29:45,550
SHE ADDS THE INGREDIENTS
INTO THE WOK

710
00:29:45,617 --> 00:29:46,851
Whoa.

711
00:29:48,253 --> 00:29:51,089
And Chef Eun-yeong
puts the ingredients into the wok.

712
00:29:52,190 --> 00:29:53,992
-My gosh.
-Wait!

713
00:29:54,058 --> 00:29:56,461
-That's so cool.
-She begins to perform!

714
00:29:57,629 --> 00:29:59,731
It's her wok performance.

715
00:30:00,698 --> 00:30:02,634
Nice to see some wok work here.

716
00:30:02,700 --> 00:30:05,236
Her performance is
not less than what Chef Hyun-suk does.

717
00:30:06,871 --> 00:30:08,973
Wok is important
when it comes to Chinese food.

718
00:30:09,040 --> 00:30:12,010
She looks so cool
when she works with the wok.

719
00:30:12,076 --> 00:30:13,278
Swish.

720
00:30:13,344 --> 00:30:15,580
Gosh, that's so cool.

721
00:30:17,515 --> 00:30:19,217
Hey, the broth.

722
00:30:19,284 --> 00:30:22,787
He can't eat it if it's too red and spicy,
so she's making White Out Soup.

723
00:30:22,854 --> 00:30:27,292
-Is it white spicy seafood soup?
-I think so. Something like that.

724
00:30:27,358 --> 00:30:29,594
I can smell something sour and delicious.

725
00:30:30,595 --> 00:30:33,464
The soup needs to look milky-white.

726
00:30:33,531 --> 00:30:36,034
That soup is thinner than I thought.

727
00:30:37,101 --> 00:30:39,470
-That's his seaweed soup.
-Yes.

728
00:30:40,772 --> 00:30:42,674
-Sung-ju. We have five minutes left.
-Yes?

729
00:30:42,740 --> 00:30:44,709
-Please report to us out in the field.
-Okay.

730
00:30:44,776 --> 00:30:48,446
Chef Hyun-suk is suffering quite a lot
because of his back pain.

731
00:30:48,513 --> 00:30:50,281
-I'm fine.
-You're fine?

732
00:30:50,348 --> 00:30:52,851
Nam-il doesn't like it
when I stage something.

733
00:30:52,917 --> 00:30:55,486
I'm totally fine.

734
00:30:56,054 --> 00:30:57,755
EVEN HIS CHARACTER IS
TAILORED TO THE GUEST

735
00:30:57,822 --> 00:30:59,657
So he looks fine for now.

736
00:30:59,724 --> 00:31:01,926
This broth seems very important.

737
00:31:01,993 --> 00:31:03,895
Oh, my. You just added some.

738
00:31:03,962 --> 00:31:07,065
Chef Hyun-suk fries
the cutlassfish once again.

739
00:31:07,131 --> 00:31:10,902
Chef Eun-yeong just turned the heat up.

740
00:31:10,969 --> 00:31:14,105
Let me… It's hot. It's so hot!

741
00:31:14,172 --> 00:31:17,308
-He can't taste it.
-Does she want to stop him?

742
00:31:17,375 --> 00:31:18,543
ONE SPOONFUL

743
00:31:18,610 --> 00:31:19,878
It's hot! Okay.

744
00:31:20,445 --> 00:31:21,613
A SIP OF THE SOUP

745
00:31:21,679 --> 00:31:25,783
Does it taste like
the soup dream will come true?

746
00:31:26,985 --> 00:31:28,653
I think the dream will break.

747
00:31:28,720 --> 00:31:29,721
Season it.

748
00:31:29,787 --> 00:31:32,757
-I think the dream will break.
-Why?

749
00:31:32,824 --> 00:31:34,826
I haven't put this in yet.
This is important.

750
00:31:34,893 --> 00:31:36,127
SHE ADDS THE IMPORTANT
OYAKODON SAUCE POWDER

751
00:31:36,194 --> 00:31:39,931
Well, it's new, but in a bad way.

752
00:31:39,998 --> 00:31:41,466
But she's the returning chef killer.

753
00:31:41,532 --> 00:31:44,202
It's like tom yum soup. It's sour.

754
00:31:44,269 --> 00:31:46,671
-Did you add too much vinegar?
-It's because he said

755
00:31:46,738 --> 00:31:49,107
he liked kimchi <i>jjigae</i>,
so I wanted to add some sour flavor.

756
00:31:49,173 --> 00:31:52,043
But the kimchi wasn't fully ripened,
so it's not too…

757
00:31:52,110 --> 00:31:54,112
-Get cooking.
-So you did it on purpose?

758
00:31:54,178 --> 00:31:57,081
Will you please cook as you talk?

759
00:31:57,649 --> 00:31:59,017
OPENS THE MICROWAVE

760
00:31:59,584 --> 00:32:01,653
MADE BRAISED RADISH
IN THE MICROWAVE

761
00:32:01,719 --> 00:32:04,923
What is that? Radish. Is it cooked well?

762
00:32:04,989 --> 00:32:06,824
-He pulled out the radish.
-Just like that?

763
00:32:06,891 --> 00:32:07,992
He braised radish like this.

764
00:32:08,793 --> 00:32:09,928
Your tooth may fall out.

765
00:32:09,994 --> 00:32:12,363
How is it?

766
00:32:12,430 --> 00:32:15,199
Can you eat that without any teeth?

767
00:32:15,767 --> 00:32:16,768
GULP

768
00:32:16,834 --> 00:32:17,969
It's delicious!

769
00:32:19,070 --> 00:32:22,540
It tastes like radish you find
in braised dishes.

770
00:32:23,241 --> 00:32:24,976
It's so cool.

771
00:32:25,043 --> 00:32:28,880
Radish doesn't become that soft
in just 15 minutes on the stovetop.

772
00:32:28,947 --> 00:32:30,782
That's a remarkable technique.

773
00:32:30,848 --> 00:32:32,850
-I may be in pain,
-Yes?

774
00:32:32,917 --> 00:32:34,152
But Nam-il must eat

775
00:32:34,218 --> 00:32:35,954
a perfect dish.

776
00:32:36,020 --> 00:32:38,089
Yes, although he isn't feeling perfect.

777
00:32:38,156 --> 00:32:39,424
You have two minutes!

778
00:32:39,490 --> 00:32:40,925
You have under two minutes.

779
00:32:40,992 --> 00:32:42,660
You have under two minutes.

780
00:32:42,727 --> 00:32:44,329
You have to season the soup right.

781
00:32:44,395 --> 00:32:45,630
You're making soup right now.

782
00:32:45,697 --> 00:32:48,633
-What is he pouring it into?
-A thermos.

783
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:50,535
What's he doing?

784
00:32:50,601 --> 00:32:53,304
-It goes in a thermos.
-He wants to keep the temperature.

785
00:32:53,371 --> 00:32:55,974
I have to serve it while it's hot.

786
00:32:56,040 --> 00:32:58,209
You want to use a thermos
to keep it hot when you serve it.

787
00:32:58,276 --> 00:33:00,778
He means that the soup should go here.

788
00:33:00,845 --> 00:33:02,180
What's that?

789
00:33:02,246 --> 00:33:05,650
-Sesame oil to add a familiar flavor.
-A clean finish.

790
00:33:05,717 --> 00:33:07,185
You need to add sesame oil
into seaweed soup.

791
00:33:07,752 --> 00:33:09,620
IN THAT WHILE,
EUN-YEONG PICKS UP AN EARTHEN POT

792
00:33:10,555 --> 00:33:12,123
ON HYUN-SUK'S STOVE

793
00:33:12,190 --> 00:33:14,092
She's using his stove.

794
00:33:14,659 --> 00:33:16,194
SHE SMOOTHLY
TAKES OVER HIS STOVE

795
00:33:16,260 --> 00:33:18,863
-You aren't using this, are you?
-Go ahead.

796
00:33:19,430 --> 00:33:21,499
He's not using it, so what?

797
00:33:21,566 --> 00:33:23,935
NO ONE CAN STOP
THIS CRAZY ZILLENNIAL WOMAN

798
00:33:24,002 --> 00:33:26,070
-I'll use this one.
-She's using the stove!

799
00:33:26,137 --> 00:33:29,941
-Chef Eun-yeong uses five stovetops.
-She's invading his stove.

800
00:33:30,008 --> 00:33:31,909
It's usually,
"You aren't using this? May I use it?"

801
00:33:31,976 --> 00:33:34,879
But she was like, "I'll use it."
There's no hierarchy!

802
00:33:34,946 --> 00:33:36,481
-Our industry has come to nothing.
-Yes.

803
00:33:36,547 --> 00:33:41,119
She uses a stick to point to this
and demand the stovetop.

804
00:33:41,185 --> 00:33:43,321
You have a minute… He's done!

805
00:33:43,388 --> 00:33:46,190
-Already? No way!
-Chef Hyun-suk is done.

806
00:33:46,257 --> 00:33:48,159
Chef Hyun-suk is done.

807
00:33:48,226 --> 00:33:50,495
Chef Hyun-suk is done,
and there's a minute left.

808
00:33:50,561 --> 00:33:53,197
-Isn't there something here?
-There is.

809
00:33:53,264 --> 00:33:55,733
-You should pull it out.
-It's cooked nicely.

810
00:33:55,800 --> 00:33:58,870
-It looks burnt.
-It doesn't smell burnt.

811
00:33:58,936 --> 00:34:01,739
I see. But it smells a bit burnt.

812
00:34:01,806 --> 00:34:03,441
You have 40 seconds left.

813
00:34:03,508 --> 00:34:07,111
She steamed three pieces
of dumplings without skin.

814
00:34:07,178 --> 00:34:10,548
-Can you pull that out?
-Okay.

815
00:34:10,615 --> 00:34:12,683
-Pull it out.
-Where should I put it?

816
00:34:12,750 --> 00:34:14,619
What's she doing?

817
00:34:14,685 --> 00:34:16,554
-Here?
-I think she's serving that.

818
00:34:16,621 --> 00:34:19,490
-Turn the heat off. Lift this.
-Wait, put it here.

819
00:34:19,557 --> 00:34:21,526
You have 23 seconds. Turn the heat off.

820
00:34:21,592 --> 00:34:22,794
What else do you need?

821
00:34:22,860 --> 00:34:25,096
She's serving the food
by putting the dumplings in.

822
00:34:25,163 --> 00:34:26,531
Fifteen seconds!

823
00:34:26,597 --> 00:34:29,734
You have 15 seconds left.
She begins to pour the soup in.

824
00:34:29,801 --> 00:34:32,603
-Nine. Eight. Seven.
-Nine. Eight. Seven.

825
00:34:32,670 --> 00:34:34,405
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

826
00:34:34,472 --> 00:34:36,441
-Four. Three.
-Four. Three.

827
00:34:36,507 --> 00:34:38,242
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

828
00:34:38,309 --> 00:34:39,410
Ring the bell!

829
00:34:39,477 --> 00:34:41,679
-She's done.
-Gosh.

830
00:34:41,746 --> 00:34:44,248
Chef Eun-yeong is done too.

831
00:34:44,315 --> 00:34:45,516
You were close.

832
00:34:45,583 --> 00:34:47,051
-My gosh.
-So close.

833
00:34:47,118 --> 00:34:48,352
-Did you miss anything?
-No.

834
00:34:48,419 --> 00:34:50,555
-Young people these days.
-You didn't miss anything.

835
00:34:50,621 --> 00:34:51,889
-Chef Eun-yeong.
-Yes?

836
00:34:51,956 --> 00:34:53,558
-Great work.
-Thank you.

837
00:34:53,624 --> 00:34:55,893
The hierarchy in the world of chefs.

838
00:34:55,960 --> 00:34:58,596
-Look how it's still boiling.
-That's nice.

839
00:34:58,663 --> 00:35:03,167
The soup dishes for Kim Nam-il
are both ready.

840
00:35:03,234 --> 00:35:05,236
I didn't know 15 minutes were this short.

841
00:35:05,303 --> 00:35:06,771
-Right?
-It flew by.

842
00:35:06,838 --> 00:35:09,073
You'll try Chef Hyun-suk's dish first.

843
00:35:09,140 --> 00:35:13,311
Will you serve the dish… Oh, no.

844
00:35:13,377 --> 00:35:14,812
-His back aches.
-Yet he's coming.

845
00:35:14,879 --> 00:35:16,781
Chef Hyun-suk comes over himself.

846
00:35:16,848 --> 00:35:18,716
My back is fine.

847
00:35:18,783 --> 00:35:20,985
Are you all right? Okay.

848
00:35:21,052 --> 00:35:22,386
He must put up with the pain.

849
00:35:22,453 --> 00:35:24,689
It's still piping hot.

850
00:35:24,755 --> 00:35:26,124
He blended the seaweed soup.

851
00:35:26,190 --> 00:35:30,428
First off, he has fried cutlassfish.

852
00:35:30,495 --> 00:35:32,497
He's pouring soup into the dish.

853
00:35:32,563 --> 00:35:34,332
THE BLENDED SEAWEED SOUP

854
00:35:35,500 --> 00:35:39,303
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
NATIONAL SEAWEED SOUP

855
00:35:39,370 --> 00:35:41,506
TOUCHED

856
00:35:41,572 --> 00:35:43,641
-Enjoy.
-Thank you.

857
00:35:45,376 --> 00:35:46,878
He smells it first.

858
00:35:46,944 --> 00:35:49,013
He loves soup.

859
00:35:49,080 --> 00:35:51,048
Seaweed soup may smell fishy.

860
00:35:51,115 --> 00:35:53,551
-It doesn't smell fishy.
-No?

861
00:35:53,618 --> 00:35:54,652
Cut everything,

862
00:35:54,719 --> 00:35:57,588
and then try the radish, cutlassfish,
and the soup together.

863
00:35:57,655 --> 00:36:00,625
-All at once?
-The soup, the fish, and the radish.

864
00:36:00,691 --> 00:36:04,896
It's seaweed soup, but it'll feel new.

865
00:36:05,463 --> 00:36:07,732
-Listen to the sound.
-He fried the cutlassfish twice.

866
00:36:07,798 --> 00:36:09,667
-It sounds so crunchy.
-It does.

867
00:36:09,734 --> 00:36:11,869
I can hear the crunchy sound
as he cuts the fish.

868
00:36:11,936 --> 00:36:13,804
-He already ate it with the knife.
-The fish.

869
00:36:13,871 --> 00:36:15,206
-It looks good.
-Try the soup

870
00:36:15,273 --> 00:36:18,342
-with your spoon.
-He's never seen anything like it.

871
00:36:18,409 --> 00:36:19,810
He has everything.

872
00:36:19,877 --> 00:36:21,245
He's taking a bite.

873
00:36:21,312 --> 00:36:23,114
He smells it first.

874
00:36:23,181 --> 00:36:24,782
He's very detailed.

875
00:36:28,920 --> 00:36:31,689
HE TAKES A BITE VERY CAREFULLY

876
00:36:32,990 --> 00:36:35,159
Since when have you eaten so carefully?

877
00:36:35,226 --> 00:36:36,627
CAREFUL

878
00:36:36,694 --> 00:36:38,296
I've never seen him like that.

879
00:36:38,362 --> 00:36:40,531
He'd usually eat just
rice and <i>sundae </i>soup.

880
00:36:40,598 --> 00:36:42,300
That was too superficial.

881
00:36:42,366 --> 00:36:43,801
He's shaking his head.

882
00:36:43,868 --> 00:36:44,936
And he nods.

883
00:36:45,002 --> 00:36:47,038
-Shaking and nodding.
-Is it all right?

884
00:36:49,373 --> 00:36:50,875
What does he mean by that?

885
00:36:50,942 --> 00:36:53,678
He tries another bite without a word,
now, just the soup.

886
00:36:53,744 --> 00:36:54,745
It looks good.

887
00:36:54,812 --> 00:36:56,180
It probably tastes good.

888
00:36:56,247 --> 00:36:59,050
It was a bit too bland
when I had just the soup.

889
00:36:59,116 --> 00:37:00,851
I wonder if it tastes okay now.

890
00:37:00,918 --> 00:37:04,155
First, the fried cutlassfish.

891
00:37:04,222 --> 00:37:06,791
-It tastes light.
-It's light.

892
00:37:06,857 --> 00:37:09,493
The radish was cooked thoroughly too.

893
00:37:09,560 --> 00:37:10,995
It's snappy.

894
00:37:11,062 --> 00:37:13,698
-Was it cooked well?
-You used the word snappy.

895
00:37:13,764 --> 00:37:15,600
-That's high praise.
-Yes.

896
00:37:15,666 --> 00:37:19,237
When Nam-il says something's snappy,
it's the highest praise.

897
00:37:19,303 --> 00:37:22,173
Snappy? What is that?

898
00:37:22,240 --> 00:37:25,910
I have to write it in my notes app.
It's a new word.

899
00:37:25,977 --> 00:37:29,146
The foreign chefs are
fascinated with that word.

900
00:37:29,213 --> 00:37:32,149
I think that's a positive response.

901
00:37:32,216 --> 00:37:36,454
I wonder if it's a new soup he wanted.
He begins to gulp it down.

902
00:37:36,520 --> 00:37:37,955
-Did he eat it all?
-He likes it.

903
00:37:38,022 --> 00:37:39,056
A THUMBS-UP

904
00:37:39,624 --> 00:37:40,758
THANK YOU

905
00:37:40,825 --> 00:37:42,627
Can you feel some seaweed?

906
00:37:42,693 --> 00:37:44,929
There are bits and pieces I can chew,

907
00:37:44,996 --> 00:37:47,865
but it mostly goes down smoothly.

908
00:37:47,932 --> 00:37:48,933
He takes another bite.

909
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:52,169
This time, he crushed the fish a little.

910
00:37:52,937 --> 00:37:54,138
A BIG BITE

911
00:37:54,205 --> 00:37:55,206
Another bite.

912
00:37:58,209 --> 00:37:59,944
Does it taste different? What's wrong?

913
00:38:00,611 --> 00:38:01,912
-Is it a bone?
-Did you chew on something?

914
00:38:01,979 --> 00:38:03,814
A bone? No way.

915
00:38:03,881 --> 00:38:06,284
The radish wasn't cooked all the way.

916
00:38:06,350 --> 00:38:08,085
Was it not cooked through and through?

917
00:38:08,152 --> 00:38:10,021
The kind of dishes I like to cook is

918
00:38:10,087 --> 00:38:12,857
something with many different textures.

919
00:38:12,923 --> 00:38:15,893
-Yes, he usually does that.
-Different textures.

920
00:38:15,960 --> 00:38:18,963
-Something new.
-Something fun.

921
00:38:19,030 --> 00:38:20,998
-He hates evenly-cooked dishes.
-No way.

922
00:38:21,065 --> 00:38:23,768
-But the soup is fine.
-The soup's fine.

923
00:38:23,834 --> 00:38:27,972
It was a type of soup
I've never had to this day.

924
00:38:28,039 --> 00:38:30,775
-What he wanted was the soup.
-All right.

925
00:38:30,841 --> 00:38:33,511
-He said it was snappy.
-He did.

926
00:38:33,577 --> 00:38:35,913
We got a positive response.

927
00:38:37,048 --> 00:38:39,583
MILKY-WHITE SOUP
MADE WITH FRIED FISH BONES

928
00:38:40,551 --> 00:38:41,652
DUMPLINGS WITHOUT SKIN

929
00:38:41,719 --> 00:38:43,854
AND WHITE KIMCHI
MADE BY HIS SISTER-IN-LAW

930
00:38:45,156 --> 00:38:48,659
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
WHITE OUT SOUP

931
00:38:49,760 --> 00:38:51,762
-Enjoy.
-Yes.

932
00:38:52,330 --> 00:38:53,464
-"Enjoy."
-"Enjoy."

933
00:38:53,531 --> 00:38:55,766
May I get a new spoon?

934
00:38:55,833 --> 00:38:57,168
So he can taste it properly.

935
00:38:57,234 --> 00:38:59,003
-Hey, Nam-il.
-I knew it.

936
00:38:59,070 --> 00:39:00,438
He wants to be precise.

937
00:39:00,504 --> 00:39:03,607
Since when did you switch between spoons?

938
00:39:03,674 --> 00:39:06,010
He's on TV.

939
00:39:06,077 --> 00:39:08,779
You should have some water
and rinse out your mouth.

940
00:39:08,846 --> 00:39:10,381
He isn't normally this meticulous.

941
00:39:10,448 --> 00:39:11,849
How should he eat this?

942
00:39:11,916 --> 00:39:15,152
Split up the dumpling

943
00:39:15,219 --> 00:39:18,155
-and try it with the soup.
-However you like.

944
00:39:18,222 --> 00:39:21,992
I wonder how Nam-il will respond.

945
00:39:22,927 --> 00:39:24,528
-It's hot.
-It's still hot.

946
00:39:24,595 --> 00:39:26,063
-You should blow on it.
-I'm sorry.

947
00:39:26,130 --> 00:39:28,999
You should've blown on it.

948
00:39:29,066 --> 00:39:31,402
Why is he mad at her?

949
00:39:31,469 --> 00:39:33,504
You should've told me it was hot.

950
00:39:33,571 --> 00:39:36,140
Anyone can see how steamy it is.

951
00:39:36,941 --> 00:39:38,776
You should've blown on it.

952
00:39:38,843 --> 00:39:40,978
That's his thing.
He starts by getting mad.

953
00:39:42,313 --> 00:39:43,381
HE CAREFULLY TAKES A BITE

954
00:39:43,447 --> 00:39:45,916
He tries the dumpling
and the soup together.

955
00:39:46,751 --> 00:39:48,753
He doesn't show
too much change on his face.

956
00:39:49,320 --> 00:39:51,989
I can taste some sourness

957
00:39:52,056 --> 00:39:54,625
-because of the kimchi.
-The sourness.

958
00:39:54,692 --> 00:39:56,627
-His sister-in-law made that, right?
-Yes.

959
00:39:56,694 --> 00:39:57,862
I used his sister-in-law's kimchi,

960
00:39:57,928 --> 00:40:00,865
and the key is that
you need to taste that bit of sourness.

961
00:40:01,532 --> 00:40:03,267
I can taste that.

962
00:40:03,334 --> 00:40:05,836
-It's like hot and sour soup.
-Yes, right.

963
00:40:05,903 --> 00:40:08,272
-It's warm yet sour.
-Yes.

964
00:40:08,339 --> 00:40:09,540
It tastes quite sour.

965
00:40:09,607 --> 00:40:12,376
-It's like hot and sour soup.
-Hot and sour soup is like that.

966
00:40:12,443 --> 00:40:15,179
Try it with the veggies.

967
00:40:16,280 --> 00:40:17,681
HE TOPS IT WITH LOTS OF VEGGIES

968
00:40:17,748 --> 00:40:18,949
My mouth is watering.

969
00:40:19,016 --> 00:40:21,452
He's a first-timer on variety shows.

970
00:40:22,019 --> 00:40:26,023
HE COOLS IT DOWN
AS MUCH AS HE CAN

971
00:40:26,090 --> 00:40:27,825
It looks good.

972
00:40:27,892 --> 00:40:31,095
He's nodding and savoring.

973
00:40:31,162 --> 00:40:33,264
-He likes this kind of taste.
-Really?

974
00:40:33,330 --> 00:40:34,765
-Gosh.
-My gosh.

975
00:40:34,832 --> 00:40:37,001
IT LOOKS LIKE HE DID "WHITE OUT"

976
00:40:37,067 --> 00:40:39,670
The soup.
It's like a scene from a commercial.

977
00:40:39,737 --> 00:40:41,172
Hey, that's hot.

978
00:40:41,238 --> 00:40:43,507
-He's so nice about it.
-He drinks the soup.

979
00:40:44,375 --> 00:40:46,310
Nice angle.

980
00:40:46,377 --> 00:40:48,479
You look a bit like Gang Dong-won.

981
00:40:48,546 --> 00:40:50,881
-Did you just say Dong-won?
-My gosh.

982
00:40:50,948 --> 00:40:52,316
It's like a <i>ramyeon</i> commercial.

983
00:40:52,383 --> 00:40:55,586
-He just chugged the soup.
-Exactly.

984
00:40:55,653 --> 00:40:57,254
He keeps talking with his eyes.

985
00:40:57,321 --> 00:41:00,157
Can you tell us in words
instead of just your eyes?

986
00:41:00,224 --> 00:41:03,794
-What's it like?
-Well, I had some soju last night.

987
00:41:03,861 --> 00:41:05,596
-I see.
-Just one glass of soju.

988
00:41:05,663 --> 00:41:07,631
So I wasn't feeling so good.

989
00:41:07,698 --> 00:41:10,267
This just helped my stomach calm down.

990
00:41:10,334 --> 00:41:12,369
-Like relieving your hangover?
-Yes.

991
00:41:12,436 --> 00:41:14,171
So it helps with your hangover?

992
00:41:14,238 --> 00:41:16,240
But do you need it
after one glass of soju?

993
00:41:16,307 --> 00:41:18,609
Goodness, he begins to wail.

994
00:41:18,676 --> 00:41:20,478
-This is nice.
-It's that sourness.

995
00:41:20,544 --> 00:41:23,013
-The dumpling without skin.
-It's excellent.

996
00:41:23,080 --> 00:41:25,115
It doesn't smell fishy or burnt.

997
00:41:25,182 --> 00:41:27,751
-Any room for improvement?
-Improvement?

998
00:41:27,818 --> 00:41:29,353
It was too hot before.

999
00:41:30,287 --> 00:41:31,989
-It was too hot.
-Yes, right.

1000
00:41:32,056 --> 00:41:34,992
-I burnt my tongue a little.
-He burnt his tongue.

1001
00:41:35,059 --> 00:41:37,761
Other than that, I don't see any problems.

1002
00:41:37,828 --> 00:41:40,197
What can she do about that?
It was your fault.

1003
00:41:40,264 --> 00:41:41,932
It's not like she can blow on it.

1004
00:41:41,999 --> 00:41:44,401
He drinks the soup once again.

1005
00:41:44,468 --> 00:41:47,805
-I think the sourness is addictive.
-Yes.

1006
00:41:47,872 --> 00:41:50,007
Let's try Chef Hyun-suk's dish first.

1007
00:41:50,074 --> 00:41:54,278
It's becoming thicker over time.

1008
00:41:54,345 --> 00:41:58,449
It may taste a bit too bland
for someone from Pohang.

1009
00:41:58,516 --> 00:41:59,517
It's not bland.

1010
00:41:59,583 --> 00:42:01,785
First off, the radish is cooked well.

1011
00:42:01,852 --> 00:42:03,521
It is. That piece was cooked well.

1012
00:42:03,587 --> 00:42:06,223
-It doesn't feel like seaweed soup.
-Right?

1013
00:42:06,290 --> 00:42:08,092
It's not like the usual seaweed soup.

1014
00:42:08,158 --> 00:42:11,161
-It's more like just soup.
-A bit thicker.

1015
00:42:11,228 --> 00:42:14,164
-The cutlassfish is almost perfect.
-The sourness.

1016
00:42:14,231 --> 00:42:17,768
-It even tastes like <i>maesaengi </i>soup.
-Yes.

1017
00:42:17,835 --> 00:42:20,604
And I liked the radish crunchy

1018
00:42:20,671 --> 00:42:23,574
<i>than when it's too soft.</i>

1019
00:42:23,641 --> 00:42:27,211
I think he meant the texture
of the radish to change over time.

1020
00:42:27,278 --> 00:42:29,246
-I think he meant it.
-Everything is nicely presented.

1021
00:42:29,313 --> 00:42:33,083
Let's try Chef Eun-yeong's White Out Soup.

1022
00:42:33,150 --> 00:42:34,485
It's good.

1023
00:42:34,552 --> 00:42:36,987
Try the soup and the dumplings.

1024
00:42:37,054 --> 00:42:39,990
-It's hot.
-It's hot, isn't it?

1025
00:42:40,057 --> 00:42:41,859
-It's hot.
-Right?

1026
00:42:41,926 --> 00:42:44,495
Soccer players are impatient,
so we're bad at eating hot food.

1027
00:42:44,562 --> 00:42:47,131
I see. You're all too rushed.

1028
00:42:47,197 --> 00:42:48,198
Does it taste sour?

1029
00:42:48,265 --> 00:42:51,502
I tried it thinking
it'd taste sour like vinegar.

1030
00:42:51,569 --> 00:42:53,971
But it was the sourness you taste
from ripened kimchi.

1031
00:42:54,038 --> 00:42:56,740
It's like kimchi <i>jjigae</i>
without the spiciness.

1032
00:42:56,807 --> 00:42:57,875
Yes, I think so.

1033
00:42:57,942 --> 00:43:00,210
-That's perfect.
-Is that it?

1034
00:43:00,277 --> 00:43:02,446
I like this kind of taste.

1035
00:43:02,513 --> 00:43:04,014
I see.

1036
00:43:04,081 --> 00:43:07,351
You must choose one of the two.

1037
00:43:07,418 --> 00:43:08,552
SPOTS HIM

1038
00:43:08,619 --> 00:43:12,056
-Nam-no, did you steal the pot?
-Yes.

1039
00:43:12,122 --> 00:43:13,490
When did you grab that?

1040
00:43:13,557 --> 00:43:15,793
It was a shame to see the leftovers, so…
It's really good.

1041
00:43:15,859 --> 00:43:17,261
What's it like?

1042
00:43:17,328 --> 00:43:20,431
It's spicier than I thought,
but it's not too pungent.

1043
00:43:20,497 --> 00:43:23,567
Everything mixes together very nicely.

1044
00:43:24,602 --> 00:43:30,574
Also, I don't know how she managed
to make this soup with such little fish.

1045
00:43:30,641 --> 00:43:32,343
I have no idea.

1046
00:43:32,409 --> 00:43:36,447
It was as if she's using soup concentrate.

1047
00:43:36,513 --> 00:43:38,215
Now, make your snappy choice.

1048
00:43:38,282 --> 00:43:39,617
TIME TO CHOOSE

1049
00:43:39,683 --> 00:43:41,318
Press one for Park Eun-yeong,

1050
00:43:41,385 --> 00:43:43,187
press two for Choi Hyun-suk.

1051
00:43:43,253 --> 00:43:46,190
Make your decision and press the button.

1052
00:43:46,890 --> 00:43:49,093
-This is a tough one.
-Yes.

1053
00:43:49,159 --> 00:43:50,995
You had fun while you tried that, right?

1054
00:43:51,729 --> 00:43:53,330
You ate so excitedly.

1055
00:43:53,397 --> 00:43:56,033
You chugged it so deliciously.

1056
00:43:56,100 --> 00:43:58,936
-He'd shake his head too.
-Just like this.

1057
00:43:59,003 --> 00:44:01,472
-He even changed his spoons.
-You enjoyed your food.

1058
00:44:01,538 --> 00:44:03,807
He's going to push it.

1059
00:44:03,874 --> 00:44:05,843
He did. All right.

1060
00:44:05,909 --> 00:44:08,479
THE DARK HORSE
VERSUS THE BEST CHEF

1061
00:44:08,545 --> 00:44:12,349
Which one of them did Nam-il choose?

1062
00:44:12,416 --> 00:44:14,618
Let's find out who the winner is.

1063
00:44:14,685 --> 00:44:16,353
It's the soup dish round.

1064
00:44:16,420 --> 00:44:18,856
The best chef on the show now,
Chef Choi Hyun-suk.

1065
00:44:18,922 --> 00:44:21,225
And the returning chef killer,
Chef Park Eun-yeong.

1066
00:44:21,291 --> 00:44:23,427
These two fought against each other
with soup dishes.

1067
00:44:23,494 --> 00:44:27,765
Who did Nam-il choose?

1068
00:44:27,831 --> 00:44:30,000
Which soup dish did you like better?

1069
00:44:30,668 --> 00:44:32,236
Soup will come true.

1070
00:44:32,870 --> 00:44:34,438
Who's the winner?

1071
00:44:34,505 --> 00:44:36,106
CHOI HYUN-SUK WINS

1072
00:44:36,173 --> 00:44:37,474
CHEF CHOI HYUN-SUK'S
NATIONAL SEAWEED SOUP WINS

1073
00:44:37,541 --> 00:44:39,243
It was Hyun-suk.

1074
00:44:39,309 --> 00:44:41,478
That was unexpected.

1075
00:44:43,213 --> 00:44:44,481
HYUN-SUK COLLAPSES

1076
00:44:44,548 --> 00:44:47,317
-Hyun-suk finally collapses.
-He falls.

1077
00:44:47,384 --> 00:44:50,421
He's done doing his job now.

1078
00:44:51,689 --> 00:44:54,391
My back, you held out very well.

1079
00:44:54,458 --> 00:44:56,627
-Thanks, my back.
-He can fall down now.

1080
00:44:57,194 --> 00:44:58,762
HE'S HAPPIER NOW
THAN WHEN HE HIT A BIRDIE

1081
00:44:58,829 --> 00:45:01,765
-That was unexpected.
-We thought it'd be Chef Eun-yeong.

1082
00:45:01,832 --> 00:45:03,734
-I thought you had decided.
-I thought so.

1083
00:45:03,801 --> 00:45:06,570
Chef Eun-yeong's dish was…

1084
00:45:06,637 --> 00:45:08,772
I'll get mad if you say it was too hot.

1085
00:45:10,274 --> 00:45:12,076
I really loved the soup.

1086
00:45:12,142 --> 00:45:15,546
<i>I loved how she made</i>
<i>the white seafood soup.</i>

1087
00:45:16,213 --> 00:45:17,381
But it tasted familiar.

1088
00:45:17,448 --> 00:45:19,516
-It was like that.
-It was familiar.

1089
00:45:19,583 --> 00:45:22,686
-A familiar flavor.
-He wanted a new kind of soup.

1090
00:45:22,753 --> 00:45:24,722
Chef Hyun-suk's dish

1091
00:45:24,788 --> 00:45:28,325
came with a great new idea.

1092
00:45:28,392 --> 00:45:30,928
I was also touched,

1093
00:45:30,994 --> 00:45:32,596
even though he could've just acted,

1094
00:45:32,663 --> 00:45:34,898
but he had that persistent spirit.

1095
00:45:34,965 --> 00:45:39,203
This means he gets to save his face
as one of the returning chefs.

1096
00:45:39,269 --> 00:45:42,773
Chef Hyun-suk wins.

1097
00:45:42,840 --> 00:45:44,708
Great job, both of you.

1098
00:45:44,775 --> 00:45:46,977
-And he did it despite his injury.
-Really?

1099
00:45:47,044 --> 00:45:48,645
That's Chef Hyun-suk's seventh victory.

1100
00:45:48,712 --> 00:45:50,647
-The first place on the show!
-I knew it!

1101
00:45:50,714 --> 00:45:52,850
Congratulations, Hyun-suk.

1102
00:45:54,384 --> 00:45:56,420
Hello, viewers.

1103
00:45:56,487 --> 00:45:58,622
We're here at <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Stadium.

1104
00:45:58,689 --> 00:46:00,891
<i>Korea versus Italy.</i>

1105
00:46:00,958 --> 00:46:02,626
<i>Italy and Korea are</i>

1106
00:46:02,693 --> 00:46:04,261
up against each other

1107
00:46:04,328 --> 00:46:10,367
to fill the order for Nam-il, titled,
"Again 2002, recharge the vacuum cleaner."

1108
00:46:10,434 --> 00:46:13,303
I'm here with Ahn Jung-hwan,
the commentator.

1109
00:46:13,370 --> 00:46:15,239
-Hello.
-Hello.

1110
00:46:15,305 --> 00:46:18,876
Fabri represents Italy,
and Poong represents Korea.

1111
00:46:18,942 --> 00:46:20,744
What do you think about this game?

1112
00:46:20,811 --> 00:46:22,946
Honestly speaking,
there's a bit of a gap in their skills.

1113
00:46:23,013 --> 00:46:24,848
-Yes.
-It's quite huge, actually.

1114
00:46:24,915 --> 00:46:26,517
Fabri from Italy

1115
00:46:26,583 --> 00:46:30,821
has kept a Michelin one-star
for his restaurant for 15 years in a row.

1116
00:46:30,888 --> 00:46:34,525
-We can say that he's one of the best.
-Yes.

1117
00:46:34,591 --> 00:46:36,026
On the other hand,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1118
00:46:36,093 --> 00:46:38,829
He's representing Korea
without any qualifications.

1119
00:46:38,896 --> 00:46:40,764
I'm sure he'll face hardships.

1120
00:46:40,831 --> 00:46:43,033
-He has lots of ups and downs.
-Yes.

1121
00:46:43,100 --> 00:46:45,769
Poong seems to have become

1122
00:46:45,836 --> 00:46:49,239
quite skillful recently.

1123
00:46:49,306 --> 00:46:53,610
His loach dish and tofu dish were

1124
00:46:53,677 --> 00:46:55,946
-both excellent.
-Weren't they?

1125
00:46:56,013 --> 00:47:00,684
That's why I'll fight him
with another crazy dish.

1126
00:47:00,751 --> 00:47:03,620
-I see.
-A crazy dish, just like Poong's style.

1127
00:47:03,687 --> 00:47:08,158
But that's not the order.
Why does he want to make a crazy dish?

1128
00:47:08,225 --> 00:47:11,061
A healthy, energetic,

1129
00:47:11,128 --> 00:47:12,729
and crazy dish.

1130
00:47:14,031 --> 00:47:16,800
I have an announcement
before this round begins.

1131
00:47:16,867 --> 00:47:19,670
Nam-il is here as a referee,

1132
00:47:19,736 --> 00:47:24,107
-What are those?
-I'll give him yellow and red cards.

1133
00:47:24,174 --> 00:47:26,276
So Nam-il will be Moreno the referee?

1134
00:47:26,343 --> 00:47:29,446
Whoever that gets a red card
must stop for five seconds.

1135
00:47:29,513 --> 00:47:31,315
Really?

1136
00:47:32,149 --> 00:47:33,917
CHEF FABRI'S INGREDIENTS: WHITE KIMCHI,
INSTANT DUCK, GRANA PADANO CHEESE, HONEY

1137
00:47:33,984 --> 00:47:35,719
DIJON MUSTARD, STRAWBERRY, KOREAN MELON,
SHINE MUSCAT, BUCKWHEAT NOODLES, AND MORE

1138
00:47:35,786 --> 00:47:38,488
The dish I prepared is called

1139
00:47:38,555 --> 00:47:39,656
Chilled-bonara.

1140
00:47:39,723 --> 00:47:42,059
-Chilled-bonara?
-Chilled-bonara?

1141
00:47:42,125 --> 00:47:43,627
Chilled-bonara.

1142
00:47:43,694 --> 00:47:45,128
-Chilled-bonara?
-Yes.

1143
00:47:45,195 --> 00:47:50,334
I'll make a chilled dish
that tastes like carbonara.

1144
00:47:50,400 --> 00:47:52,402
-Cold carbonara?
-I'll make that.

1145
00:47:52,469 --> 00:47:54,137
He's pretty much Korean now.

1146
00:47:54,204 --> 00:47:59,943
And when Italian soccer team
wants to recharge on energy,

1147
00:48:00,010 --> 00:48:02,279
they eat lots of eggs and cheese.

1148
00:48:02,346 --> 00:48:06,984
But that can get a bit too greasy,

1149
00:48:07,050 --> 00:48:11,822
so I'll mix kimchi and fruit
to make some salad.

1150
00:48:11,889 --> 00:48:13,323
Hey, that sounds good.

1151
00:48:13,390 --> 00:48:15,826
-That's the side dish.
-The side dish. Anything else?

1152
00:48:15,893 --> 00:48:18,328
Yes, I'll make dessert too.

1153
00:48:18,395 --> 00:48:21,765
My dessert is yogurt and Chinese yams.

1154
00:48:21,832 --> 00:48:24,935
-Chinese yams?
-He said he liked Chinese yams.

1155
00:48:25,002 --> 00:48:26,203
Yams sound appetizing.

1156
00:48:26,270 --> 00:48:29,673
He'll make three dishes
in that short while.

1157
00:48:29,740 --> 00:48:31,642
I'm not sure if I'll do well.

1158
00:48:32,576 --> 00:48:34,411
WEBTOON ARTIST POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
PORK SHOULDER, TOMATO SAUCE

1159
00:48:34,478 --> 00:48:36,313
LEMON JUICE, HONEY,
THIN NOODLES, TSUYU

1160
00:48:36,380 --> 00:48:38,482
The name of my dish is this.

1161
00:48:39,816 --> 00:48:41,752
The Gentleman Sucks.

1162
00:48:43,220 --> 00:48:46,189
-Wait.
-Wait, he gets carded.

1163
00:48:46,256 --> 00:48:49,159
-The Gentleman Sucks.
-No.

1164
00:48:49,226 --> 00:48:53,797
Are you making fun
of <i>The Gentlemen's League</i>?

1165
00:48:54,398 --> 00:48:55,966
What's The Gentleman Sucks?

1166
00:48:56,033 --> 00:48:58,001
Please hear me out.

1167
00:48:58,068 --> 00:49:01,705
What's Nam-il's nickname?
He's the vacuum cleaner.

1168
00:49:01,772 --> 00:49:04,608
-Yes.
-Oh, sucking in.

1169
00:49:04,675 --> 00:49:06,443
-Oh, "to suck in."
-I'm also making

1170
00:49:06,510 --> 00:49:09,479
cold noodles today.

1171
00:49:09,546 --> 00:49:12,849
I'll make noodles
that represent the color red.

1172
00:49:12,916 --> 00:49:14,384
-Red?
-That's what I'll make.

1173
00:49:14,451 --> 00:49:15,552
-Like spicy noodles.
-Yes.

1174
00:49:15,619 --> 00:49:18,055
-He said he didn't like spicy food.
-No.

1175
00:49:18,121 --> 00:49:21,458
I'll use tomato pasta sauce

1176
00:49:21,525 --> 00:49:24,761
and make noodles
full of healthy tomato flavor.

1177
00:49:24,828 --> 00:49:27,998
-Sounds good.
-Here's the important thing.

1178
00:49:28,065 --> 00:49:30,867
I'll make it so
that you can suck on it with a straw.

1179
00:49:30,934 --> 00:49:33,403
-What?
-With a straw?

1180
00:49:33,470 --> 00:49:35,172
He has to suck on spicy noodles?

1181
00:49:35,238 --> 00:49:36,907
I CAN'T HOLD BACK MY RED CARD

1182
00:49:38,275 --> 00:49:41,445
I don't have enough energy
to suck on anything.

1183
00:49:41,511 --> 00:49:42,713
He has no energy to suck on it.

1184
00:49:42,779 --> 00:49:44,214
-Wait.
-Isn't this another crazy dish?

1185
00:49:44,281 --> 00:49:45,649
He has to suck on noodles?

1186
00:49:45,716 --> 00:49:47,451
-How will he do that?
-I mean…

1187
00:49:47,517 --> 00:49:51,121
Nam-il of all people can suck it.

1188
00:49:51,188 --> 00:49:52,589
On noodles.

1189
00:49:52,656 --> 00:49:55,192
He'll get high blood pressure
because he has no energy.

1190
00:49:55,258 --> 00:49:56,793
You'll get high blood pressure

1191
00:49:56,860 --> 00:49:59,830
and begin to feel uplifted,
then reaching a dopamine hit.

1192
00:49:59,896 --> 00:50:02,532
-You can suck it in.
-I'm convinced.

1193
00:50:02,599 --> 00:50:05,836
He's right. He can get more energy
with the power of sucking.

1194
00:50:05,902 --> 00:50:07,604
You're right. With the power of sucking.

1195
00:50:07,671 --> 00:50:11,742
This is something
that'll make Nam-il passionate again.

1196
00:50:11,808 --> 00:50:15,379
I made it thinking this was something
that'll make his blood boil.

1197
00:50:15,445 --> 00:50:16,880
Please look forward to it.

1198
00:50:16,947 --> 00:50:19,583
Chilled-bonara versus The Gentleman Sucks.

1199
00:50:20,150 --> 00:50:22,486
THE DISH NAMES OF THIS ROUND ARE
ALREADY EXTRAORDINARY

1200
00:50:22,552 --> 00:50:28,058
And now, let us begin the round to make
energy-recharging dishes for Nam-il.

1201
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:30,394
It's a battle between countries.

1202
00:50:30,460 --> 00:50:31,995
-This is the A-match.
-How cool.

1203
00:50:32,062 --> 00:50:34,364
He wants to score
the golden goal in cooking

1204
00:50:34,431 --> 00:50:36,566
and become the Ahn Jung-hwan among chefs.

1205
00:50:36,633 --> 00:50:40,704
Italian fantasista, Chef Fabri.

1206
00:50:40,771 --> 00:50:42,739
He's here to drag Italy
into the ditch once again

1207
00:50:42,806 --> 00:50:46,276
with his dish of darkness
in the Red Devils spirit.

1208
00:50:46,343 --> 00:50:49,846
The hot temper of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>,
Kim Poong, is up against him.

1209
00:50:49,913 --> 00:50:52,983
Gli Azzurri
versus knockoff Taegeuk Warrior.

1210
00:50:53,050 --> 00:50:57,287
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1211
00:50:59,089 --> 00:51:00,090
ITALY VS KOREA

1212
00:51:00,157 --> 00:51:01,625
It's a fight between countries.

1213
00:51:01,691 --> 00:51:04,594
Poong will represent Korea
for the next 15 minutes.

1214
00:51:04,661 --> 00:51:06,630
He's up against Fabri from Italy.

1215
00:51:06,696 --> 00:51:09,866
Objectively speaking,
Fabri definitely has a lead.

1216
00:51:09,933 --> 00:51:12,702
Poong is adding something to the blender.

1217
00:51:12,769 --> 00:51:15,238
I'm using tomato sauce as my base

1218
00:51:15,305 --> 00:51:16,873
for the noodles.

1219
00:51:16,940 --> 00:51:18,408
-I'm looking forward to it.
-Wait.

1220
00:51:18,475 --> 00:51:20,911
Can he suck on the noodles with the straw?

1221
00:51:20,977 --> 00:51:22,546
-Isn't it too thin?
-It's too thin.

1222
00:51:22,612 --> 00:51:23,980
-Can it go in?
-I think he'll cut it.

1223
00:51:24,047 --> 00:51:25,048
Even so…

1224
00:51:25,115 --> 00:51:28,051
-Did you just throw in honey?
-Yes.

1225
00:51:28,118 --> 00:51:31,254
Will Poong create another miracle today?

1226
00:51:31,321 --> 00:51:35,158
His strategy is that
he always catches the opponent off guard.

1227
00:51:35,225 --> 00:51:37,694
-And that's when he scores a goal.
-Yes.

1228
00:51:37,761 --> 00:51:39,496
-It's his strategy.
-He adds ice cubes.

1229
00:51:39,563 --> 00:51:42,165
-He's adding ice cubes there?
-The spicy noodles.

1230
00:51:42,232 --> 00:51:43,900
-Wouldn't it make the sauce bland?
-The sauce?

1231
00:51:43,967 --> 00:51:45,735
It'll look like Slurpee.

1232
00:51:45,802 --> 00:51:48,338
-He's making the sauce.
-It's like Slurpee.

1233
00:51:48,405 --> 00:51:51,741
It's not exactly like Slurpee,
but it has to be cold to taste good.

1234
00:51:51,808 --> 00:51:56,046
And everything blends very nicely.
The blender is working smoothly.

1235
00:51:58,081 --> 00:52:01,218
FABRI GRABS PLATES FIRST

1236
00:52:01,284 --> 00:52:04,488
Fabri is grating lots of cheese.

1237
00:52:04,554 --> 00:52:06,723
Do you need that much cheese?

1238
00:52:06,790 --> 00:52:07,924
Yes, you're right.

1239
00:52:07,991 --> 00:52:10,527
He says the Italian team
recharges with eggs and cheese.

1240
00:52:10,594 --> 00:52:12,496
I think he's making a cheese chip.

1241
00:52:12,562 --> 00:52:13,663
Cheese chip?

1242
00:52:14,231 --> 00:52:15,365
WHAT'S THE NEXT INGREDIENT?

1243
00:52:15,432 --> 00:52:16,800
CUTTING

1244
00:52:16,867 --> 00:52:19,102
Hey, what's that?

1245
00:52:19,169 --> 00:52:20,504
-Duck?
-Duck.

1246
00:52:20,570 --> 00:52:22,739
-Duck.
-It's something that gives you energy.

1247
00:52:22,806 --> 00:52:27,144
-Has it been smoked?
-Yes, you're right. It's smoked duck.

1248
00:52:27,210 --> 00:52:29,246
I'll use it like guanciale.

1249
00:52:29,312 --> 00:52:30,680
-Guanciale?
-Yes.

1250
00:52:30,747 --> 00:52:34,251
-It even looks similar.
-You're right.

1251
00:52:34,317 --> 00:52:37,120
He's using some duck right now.

1252
00:52:37,187 --> 00:52:38,522
It smells excellent.

1253
00:52:38,588 --> 00:52:40,056
<i>Go, Korea!</i>

1254
00:52:40,123 --> 00:52:41,625
AUTOMATIC RESPONSE

1255
00:52:41,691 --> 00:52:43,059
<i>Go, Korea!</i>

1256
00:52:45,362 --> 00:52:48,031
Poong is in high spirits.

1257
00:52:48,098 --> 00:52:51,001
-<i>Go, Korea!</i>
-He's in rhythm.

1258
00:52:51,067 --> 00:52:54,371
Why don't we all go together?
One, two, three, four.

1259
00:52:54,437 --> 00:52:56,239
<i>-Go, Korea!</i>
<i>-Go, Korea!</i>

1260
00:52:56,306 --> 00:52:57,541
EVERYONE SHOUTS AS ONE

1261
00:52:57,607 --> 00:52:59,509
That was an excellent rhythm.

1262
00:53:01,678 --> 00:53:04,114
-Did he cut it?
-It wasn't cut.

1263
00:53:04,181 --> 00:53:06,349
-Is that pork?
-Yes.

1264
00:53:06,416 --> 00:53:08,618
Can he suck out
such thick pork with a straw?

1265
00:53:09,553 --> 00:53:11,054
-Shouldn't you cut it?
-Yes, right.

1266
00:53:11,121 --> 00:53:13,557
No, I'll roast the pork.

1267
00:53:13,623 --> 00:53:15,659
He'll have to suck on the sauce
and chew on that.

1268
00:53:15,725 --> 00:53:18,328
Isn't that still too thick?

1269
00:53:18,395 --> 00:53:20,931
Poong continues to season the meat.

1270
00:53:21,598 --> 00:53:23,166
Are those grapes?

1271
00:53:23,233 --> 00:53:25,602
-Yes, grapes.
-Grapes.

1272
00:53:26,169 --> 00:53:29,039
LAST WEEK, MR. SLOW ITALIAN
REMOVED THE SEED ONE AFTER ANOTHER

1273
00:53:29,105 --> 00:53:32,042
WILL HE BE ANY DIFFERENT
THIS WEEK?

1274
00:53:32,108 --> 00:53:33,510
The Korean melon.

1275
00:53:33,577 --> 00:53:35,111
Fabri is using Korean melon.

1276
00:53:35,178 --> 00:53:36,313
Gosh.

1277
00:53:36,379 --> 00:53:37,714
Oh, no.

1278
00:53:38,848 --> 00:53:41,952
No. The Korean melon.

1279
00:53:42,452 --> 00:53:43,486
Gosh. Which way?

1280
00:53:43,553 --> 00:53:44,988
This way.

1281
00:53:45,055 --> 00:53:47,624
Why did you leave in some peels?

1282
00:53:47,691 --> 00:53:48,959
-The peels?
-For color.

1283
00:53:49,025 --> 00:53:50,293
-For color.
-For color.

1284
00:53:50,360 --> 00:53:53,096
-He removed the seeds.
-To make it prettier?

1285
00:53:53,163 --> 00:53:54,164
It was to add color.

1286
00:53:54,231 --> 00:53:57,267
He left behind some yellow
to add some color.

1287
00:53:57,334 --> 00:53:59,002
He's moving quickly right now.

1288
00:53:59,069 --> 00:54:00,303
It looks pretty.

1289
00:54:00,904 --> 00:54:02,072
What's that?

1290
00:54:02,138 --> 00:54:04,341
The white kimchi his sister-in-law made.

1291
00:54:07,210 --> 00:54:08,645
Look at him chop.

1292
00:54:08,712 --> 00:54:11,915
Anyone can see Fabri had actual training.

1293
00:54:11,982 --> 00:54:15,385
But look at how Poong scoops out flour.

1294
00:54:15,452 --> 00:54:18,455
Where did he learn to cook?

1295
00:54:18,521 --> 00:54:20,590
-Anyone can see he's an amateur.
-Yes.

1296
00:54:20,657 --> 00:54:22,192
I think he'll deep-fry the meat.

1297
00:54:22,259 --> 00:54:24,160
-You'll deep-fry it?
-It'll look like that, but it's griddling.

1298
00:54:24,227 --> 00:54:27,163
-He's velveting it.
-He is?

1299
00:54:27,230 --> 00:54:29,399
But even a properly trained chef

1300
00:54:29,466 --> 00:54:32,168
can go down by an amateur's dish.

1301
00:54:32,235 --> 00:54:34,537
Fabri uses different kinds of vegetables.

1302
00:54:34,604 --> 00:54:37,240
3. JULIENNE AND SALT GRAPES,
KOREAN MELON, WHITE KIMCHI AND APPLE

1303
00:54:37,307 --> 00:54:39,242
He has the sauce ready.

1304
00:54:39,309 --> 00:54:41,344
Poong made his thick sauce.

1305
00:54:41,411 --> 00:54:42,412
The color looks spicy.

1306
00:54:42,479 --> 00:54:44,114
Already?

1307
00:54:44,180 --> 00:54:45,448
MIXING

1308
00:54:45,515 --> 00:54:47,817
-You have under nine minutes now.
-Perilla leaf?

1309
00:54:47,884 --> 00:54:49,519
Yes, perilla leaves.

1310
00:54:49,586 --> 00:54:52,055
I love these.

1311
00:54:52,122 --> 00:54:54,924
Fabri likes the smell of perilla leaves.

1312
00:54:54,991 --> 00:54:57,260
-Yes, it smells wonderful.
-Yes.

1313
00:54:57,327 --> 00:54:59,763
To me, it's the fragrance
of Korean cuisine.

1314
00:55:01,298 --> 00:55:02,899
-Dijon mustard?
-Yes.

1315
00:55:04,567 --> 00:55:09,205
4. MIX DIJON MUSTARD,
WHITE KIMCHI JUICE AND OLIVE OIL

1316
00:55:09,272 --> 00:55:11,341
HE'S DONE WITH SALAD DRESSING

1317
00:55:13,510 --> 00:55:14,511
HE BREAKS THE THIN NOODLES?

1318
00:55:14,577 --> 00:55:16,613
-The noodles?
-What's he doing with the noodles?

1319
00:55:16,680 --> 00:55:18,748
I have to break them
to make it easier for him to suck.

1320
00:55:18,815 --> 00:55:20,617
-What?
-Make it easier to suck?

1321
00:55:20,684 --> 00:55:22,552
But the fun of eating noodles is

1322
00:55:22,619 --> 00:55:24,854
keeping them in long strands.

1323
00:55:24,921 --> 00:55:27,123
I don't get why you'll break those
and make him suck on them.

1324
00:55:27,190 --> 00:55:29,359
-It'll give an interesting texture.
-Yes.

1325
00:55:30,860 --> 00:55:32,762
-He's frying the noodles.
-No, he's boiling them.

1326
00:55:32,829 --> 00:55:34,097
-Is he?
-Is he?

1327
00:55:34,164 --> 00:55:36,399
If he fries the noodles,
it'll be impossible to suck on it.

1328
00:55:36,466 --> 00:55:37,634
Even if he does,

1329
00:55:37,701 --> 00:55:39,536
they'll get stuck in his throat.

1330
00:55:39,602 --> 00:55:41,705
He can't fry those.

1331
00:55:42,639 --> 00:55:45,008
-Wait, right here.
-What?

1332
00:55:45,075 --> 00:55:46,509
Where are the eggs?

1333
00:55:46,576 --> 00:55:48,345
-Behind you.
-Where are the eggs?

1334
00:55:48,411 --> 00:55:51,715
Why are you asking us? You should manage.

1335
00:55:51,781 --> 00:55:54,784
Italian players eat eggs
to get more energy.

1336
00:55:54,851 --> 00:55:57,887
-Italy is in trouble.
-He left the shells in.

1337
00:55:57,954 --> 00:55:58,955
GETS UP

1338
00:55:59,022 --> 00:56:01,624
The egg shells.

1339
00:56:01,691 --> 00:56:02,992
Where are you going?

1340
00:56:03,059 --> 00:56:04,361
He left the egg shells in.

1341
00:56:04,427 --> 00:56:06,696
SUMMONING HIS ITALIAN TRAUMA

1342
00:56:07,897 --> 00:56:10,166
FABRI DIDN'T SEE
THE REFEREE COMING

1343
00:56:10,233 --> 00:56:13,036
Nam-il is about to card him.

1344
00:56:13,103 --> 00:56:14,838
It's a warning.

1345
00:56:15,405 --> 00:56:16,873
It's a warning for the egg shells.

1346
00:56:16,940 --> 00:56:19,776
-Yes, hygiene is important.
-Yes.

1347
00:56:19,843 --> 00:56:22,679
He can't add egg shells into his food.

1348
00:56:22,746 --> 00:56:24,047
Fabri gets a warning.

1349
00:56:24,114 --> 00:56:26,049
HE ADDS WHITE KIMCHI JUICE
INTO EGGS?

1350
00:56:26,116 --> 00:56:29,519
He just mixed
white kimchi water and egg yolks.

1351
00:56:29,586 --> 00:56:31,788
-He did.
-Is that kimchi juice?

1352
00:56:31,855 --> 00:56:34,190
-What's that mix?
-It was white kimchi juice.

1353
00:56:34,257 --> 00:56:36,059
What kind of combination is that?

1354
00:56:36,126 --> 00:56:37,927
I think that'll be
the carbonara sauce base.

1355
00:56:37,994 --> 00:56:39,662
-That?
-That one?

1356
00:56:39,729 --> 00:56:42,499
He's double boiling that
to turn it into sauce.

1357
00:56:42,565 --> 00:56:47,237
-We usually use lemon juice.
-Instead of lemon, he uses kimchi juice.

1358
00:56:47,303 --> 00:56:49,072
-It also has that sourness.
-I see.

1359
00:56:49,139 --> 00:56:50,640
Is that getting cooked?

1360
00:56:50,707 --> 00:56:54,344
It'll turn into a cream-like texture,
almost like foam.

1361
00:56:56,513 --> 00:56:58,281
POONG'S PAN IS BUBBLING

1362
00:56:58,348 --> 00:56:59,349
TURNS QUICKLY

1363
00:57:00,083 --> 00:57:02,051
He's in a frenzy.

1364
00:57:02,118 --> 00:57:03,787
HE EVACUATES THE PAN FIRST!

1365
00:57:04,354 --> 00:57:05,355
PULL IT TOGETHER!

1366
00:57:07,791 --> 00:57:09,893
3. COAT VELVET
SEASONED PORK SHOULDER

1367
00:57:09,959 --> 00:57:11,694
WITH FRYING POWDER AND DEEP-FRY

1368
00:57:11,761 --> 00:57:13,096
Poong, it's bubbling.

1369
00:57:13,163 --> 00:57:14,664
Cold water.

1370
00:57:14,731 --> 00:57:16,533
-Cold water.
-It's next to you.

1371
00:57:18,301 --> 00:57:19,536
Why won't it get cooked?

1372
00:57:20,103 --> 00:57:21,371
HE GETS SLOWER

1373
00:57:21,438 --> 00:57:22,439
It won't get cooked so soon.

1374
00:57:22,505 --> 00:57:24,507
Fabri seems to be in trouble.

1375
00:57:24,574 --> 00:57:26,743
-It should be getting thicker.
-Yes.

1376
00:57:26,810 --> 00:57:27,877
HANG IN THERE, FOREARM

1377
00:57:27,944 --> 00:57:30,413
You have six minutes or so now.

1378
00:57:30,480 --> 00:57:32,949
You have 6 minutes and 40 seconds.

1379
00:57:33,516 --> 00:57:35,051
6 MINUTES ALREADY?

1380
00:57:35,118 --> 00:57:36,453
Gyeong-jun.

1381
00:57:37,921 --> 00:57:39,722
TIME FLIES, GOSH

1382
00:57:43,493 --> 00:57:46,029
-It's cooked.
-It's done.

1383
00:57:46,095 --> 00:57:47,397
You have 6 minutes and 40 seconds.

1384
00:57:47,464 --> 00:57:50,333
Poong is frying the pork until it's crisp.

1385
00:57:51,234 --> 00:57:52,569
It's overflowing again.

1386
00:57:52,635 --> 00:57:54,103
And he pulls the meat out.

1387
00:57:54,170 --> 00:57:56,473
Isn't it overcooked?

1388
00:57:56,539 --> 00:57:59,008
How will he eat that with a straw?

1389
00:57:59,075 --> 00:58:01,311
Maybe he has to suck on the oil.

1390
00:58:02,045 --> 00:58:03,279
SHAKING IN FEAR

1391
00:58:03,346 --> 00:58:05,515
Are you using just the oil, not the meat?

1392
00:58:05,582 --> 00:58:06,816
Yes.

1393
00:58:06,883 --> 00:58:08,885
-You're using just the lard?
-Just the lard?

1394
00:58:08,952 --> 00:58:10,854
Yes, I'm using the meat! Why wouldn't I?

1395
00:58:10,920 --> 00:58:14,491
-Will you crush those?
-Can he suck on it?

1396
00:58:14,557 --> 00:58:16,759
Even if he crushed those,
he couldn't suck on that with a straw.

1397
00:58:16,826 --> 00:58:17,961
THE EGG SAUCE
HE WORKED SO HARD ON

1398
00:58:18,027 --> 00:58:22,866
Fabri just serves that sauce in a cup.

1399
00:58:22,932 --> 00:58:24,567
It's the egg sauce for carbonara.

1400
00:58:24,634 --> 00:58:27,504
Fabri put the carbonara egg sauce
into a cup.

1401
00:58:27,570 --> 00:58:30,106
He's serving it like salad dressing.

1402
00:58:30,173 --> 00:58:31,541
You have six minutes now.

1403
00:58:31,608 --> 00:58:32,642
THE BUCKWHEAT NOODLES GO IN!

1404
00:58:33,209 --> 00:58:35,512
IN!

1405
00:58:36,446 --> 00:58:38,114
THE PAN CONTINUES TO BUBBLE

1406
00:58:38,181 --> 00:58:39,516
Come on! It keeps overflowing.

1407
00:58:39,582 --> 00:58:41,451
HE ADDS MORE COLD WATER!

1408
00:58:41,951 --> 00:58:42,952
IN THE END, IT'S SWITCHED OUT

1409
00:58:43,019 --> 00:58:44,320
-It's done.
-It's done.

1410
00:58:44,387 --> 00:58:45,989
Can he really suck on those noodles?

1411
00:58:46,723 --> 00:58:48,258
His soul is getting sucked out.

1412
00:58:48,324 --> 00:58:50,627
Poong has to finish first

1413
00:58:50,693 --> 00:58:53,763
to make him suck on the noodles
before it gets soggy.

1414
00:58:53,830 --> 00:58:55,398
Yes, it'll be impossible
when it gets soggy.

1415
00:58:55,465 --> 00:58:57,133
He must end first before Fabri.

1416
00:58:57,200 --> 00:58:58,935
Wait.

1417
00:59:00,403 --> 00:59:02,038
THE SALTED KIMCHI
AND FRUIT SALAD

1418
00:59:02,605 --> 00:59:03,673
You've got this!

1419
00:59:04,407 --> 00:59:06,242
What's that sauce?

1420
00:59:06,309 --> 00:59:08,945
It's like mustard and kimchi juice.

1421
00:59:09,012 --> 00:59:12,248
-That must be the side dish.
-It looks good.

1422
00:59:12,315 --> 00:59:14,350
-That's the side dish to the carbonara.
-It looks good.

1423
00:59:15,018 --> 00:59:16,753
Oh, no. This isn't it.

1424
00:59:16,819 --> 00:59:20,924
-He's good at using Korean ingredients.
-He adds more kimchi juice.

1425
00:59:22,258 --> 00:59:25,695
KIMCHI AND FRUIT SALAD
IS FINISHED

1426
00:59:28,598 --> 00:59:29,933
What?

1427
00:59:29,999 --> 00:59:33,069
What's that? He poured in the lard
he used to fry pork once again.

1428
00:59:33,136 --> 00:59:35,438
-Is he reusing it?
-He poured it back in.

1429
00:59:35,505 --> 00:59:36,606
Isn't that too dirty?

1430
00:59:36,673 --> 00:59:38,908
Referee Nam-il walks out again.

1431
00:59:39,375 --> 00:59:40,376
IT'S CLEAN

1432
00:59:41,477 --> 00:59:43,112
KIM POONG, RED CARD

1433
00:59:43,179 --> 00:59:45,582
He's gotten a red card.

1434
00:59:46,482 --> 00:59:49,085
IT'S MY TIME! ITALY CHARGES

1435
00:59:50,620 --> 00:59:53,156
-Five seconds!
-Five seconds!

1436
00:59:53,222 --> 00:59:54,857
-Four. Three.
-Four. Three.

1437
00:59:54,924 --> 00:59:56,726
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

1438
00:59:56,793 --> 00:59:59,028
-You can continue.
-Come on.

1439
00:59:59,095 --> 01:00:00,630
You have five minutes.

1440
01:00:00,697 --> 01:00:03,399
-Jung-hwan, please go out.
-Okay.

1441
01:00:03,466 --> 01:00:04,500
Five minutes left.

1442
01:00:04,567 --> 01:00:07,003
Italy versus Korea. Korea versus Italy.

1443
01:00:08,071 --> 01:00:09,372
Why not?

1444
01:00:09,439 --> 01:00:12,308
-He wants to drop Italy again.
-It's okay.

1445
01:00:12,375 --> 01:00:16,245
-No.
-I'm a commentator, so it's okay.

1446
01:00:16,312 --> 01:00:17,580
Fabri chops a banana.

1447
01:00:17,647 --> 01:00:20,049
You're cooking bacon…
No, it's duck, not bacon. Right?

1448
01:00:20,116 --> 01:00:22,085
One side uses duck, the other uses pork.

1449
01:00:22,151 --> 01:00:25,121
If you make the pork this crispy,

1450
01:00:25,188 --> 01:00:27,790
-you'll make him lose his teeth.
-He's frying those twice.

1451
01:00:27,857 --> 01:00:29,592
-Will it be okay?
-It's fine.

1452
01:00:29,659 --> 01:00:30,660
He's using lard.

1453
01:00:30,727 --> 01:00:33,529
-I can't eat it with a straw.
-Right?

1454
01:00:33,596 --> 01:00:34,931
Okay, then. This sauce.

1455
01:00:34,998 --> 01:00:38,167
-Let me try the noodle sauce.
-Yes, right. The sauce.

1456
01:00:38,234 --> 01:00:40,403
-It looks a bit spicy.
-Yes.

1457
01:00:40,470 --> 01:00:42,171
He takes a bite.

1458
01:00:42,238 --> 01:00:44,607
So? Would he be able to play full-time?

1459
01:00:44,674 --> 01:00:46,542
He doesn't look so happy.

1460
01:00:46,609 --> 01:00:48,277
Would he be able to play full-time?

1461
01:00:48,344 --> 01:00:50,446
I think he'll only get 30 minutes.

1462
01:00:50,513 --> 01:00:52,649
Thirty minutes? That's too little.

1463
01:00:52,715 --> 01:00:54,350
-It's odd.
-It's not spicy enough.

1464
01:00:54,417 --> 01:00:57,153
-I personally know Nam-il's palate.
-Yes.

1465
01:00:57,220 --> 01:00:59,489
-I wish it were spicier.
-Darn it.

1466
01:00:59,555 --> 01:01:01,758
-It's not spicy at all.
-He's pouring in red pepper powder.

1467
01:01:01,824 --> 01:01:03,059
It's like kimchi <i>jjigae</i>.

1468
01:01:03,126 --> 01:01:05,228
-He pours lots of powder in!
-No!

1469
01:01:05,294 --> 01:01:07,930
-He pours lots of powder in!
-No!

1470
01:01:10,166 --> 01:01:12,435
-You're responsible!
-It's not that.

1471
01:01:12,502 --> 01:01:15,738
He likes it when his food is
about as spicy as kimchi <i>jjigae</i>.

1472
01:01:15,805 --> 01:01:18,908
-Okay.
-That was just sweet and sour.

1473
01:01:18,975 --> 01:01:22,111
-It didn't have spiciness. He needs that.
-Okay.

1474
01:01:22,178 --> 01:01:24,347
As we speak, he brings out Chinese yams.

1475
01:01:24,414 --> 01:01:28,017
-Chinese yams, my favorite.
-Fabri works on it.

1476
01:01:31,154 --> 01:01:33,256
HIS CHOPPING SPEED
IS AT THE HIGHEST!

1477
01:01:34,123 --> 01:01:35,458
THE CHOPPING SKILLS

1478
01:01:35,525 --> 01:01:37,593
OF A MICHELIN ONE-STAR CHEF
FOR 15 CONSECUTIVE YEARS

1479
01:01:37,660 --> 01:01:40,163
Fabri is about to blend the Chinese yams.

1480
01:01:40,229 --> 01:01:42,065
BANANA AND YOGURT, CHINESE YAMS

1481
01:01:42,565 --> 01:01:45,735
Look at this. Strawberries and honey.

1482
01:01:45,802 --> 01:01:48,271
6. BLEND BANANA, GREEK YOGURT,

1483
01:01:48,337 --> 01:01:50,339
CHINESE YAMS, STRAWBERRIES,
AND HONEY

1484
01:01:51,307 --> 01:01:52,875
FABRI IS MUCH FASTER
THAN LAST WEEK

1485
01:01:52,942 --> 01:01:53,976
Excuse me.

1486
01:01:54,544 --> 01:01:56,479
HE'S DONE
WITH THE BUCKWHEAT NOODLES

1487
01:01:57,613 --> 01:01:59,549
HE HAS 2 MINUTES
AND 30 SECONDS LEFT

1488
01:02:01,617 --> 01:02:04,253
POONG IS ABOUT
TO FINISH UP HIS NOODLES

1489
01:02:04,320 --> 01:02:05,488
Sesame oil.

1490
01:02:06,789 --> 01:02:11,060
4. ADD SESAME OIL
TO THE NOODLE SAUCE

1491
01:02:12,662 --> 01:02:13,663
Look at that.

1492
01:02:15,264 --> 01:02:18,334
To make him suck it in? Can he do that?

1493
01:02:18,401 --> 01:02:20,937
The noodles…

1494
01:02:21,003 --> 01:02:21,904
What?

1495
01:02:21,971 --> 01:02:25,441
The meat is turning into ashes.

1496
01:02:25,508 --> 01:02:27,176
The texture is probably…

1497
01:02:27,243 --> 01:02:29,979
-Jung-hwan, can you check on the pork?
-Yes?

1498
01:02:30,046 --> 01:02:31,681
AN INTERIM CHECK
ON THE FRIED PORK SHOULDER

1499
01:02:31,748 --> 01:02:32,982
SIZZLING

1500
01:02:33,049 --> 01:02:34,951
I think he should flush this one too.

1501
01:02:35,752 --> 01:02:37,453
It looks too dark.

1502
01:02:37,520 --> 01:02:40,356
-It's almost…
-No, it's perfect.

1503
01:02:41,057 --> 01:02:42,759
-Will you throw it out?
-Blend it?

1504
01:02:42,825 --> 01:02:44,660
-What are you doing?
-I didn't see the middle.

1505
01:02:44,727 --> 01:02:46,062
I need a strainer.

1506
01:02:46,129 --> 01:02:48,131
Where are you going, Poong?

1507
01:02:48,197 --> 01:02:49,198
-I need this.
-Hey.

1508
01:02:49,265 --> 01:02:51,934
That's cheating. Red card!

1509
01:02:52,935 --> 01:02:55,471
PRETENDING LIKE HE DIDN'T SEE IT

1510
01:02:55,538 --> 01:02:56,572
That was cheating!

1511
01:02:56,639 --> 01:02:58,908
Another red card.

1512
01:02:59,942 --> 01:03:02,578
-It's like going to the opponent's bench.
-The referee lets it slide.

1513
01:03:02,645 --> 01:03:05,148
It's like going to the opponent's bench.

1514
01:03:05,214 --> 01:03:06,215
TURNING HIS HEAD AWAY

1515
01:03:07,383 --> 01:03:10,686
HE PUTS THE PORK SHOULDER
OVER THE STRAINER

1516
01:03:11,521 --> 01:03:13,856
-I see some cooked noodles.
-Yes?

1517
01:03:13,923 --> 01:03:15,224
Should I suck it with a straw?

1518
01:03:15,291 --> 01:03:16,626
-Yes.
-Should I check if I can do it?

1519
01:03:16,692 --> 01:03:18,528
-I'll suck on it.
-Okay.

1520
01:03:18,594 --> 01:03:20,229
I don't think it'll work.

1521
01:03:20,296 --> 01:03:21,430
The straw is too thin.

1522
01:03:21,497 --> 01:03:23,065
-He can't suck on it.
-So?

1523
01:03:23,132 --> 01:03:25,134
You have 1 minute and 20 seconds.
Can you suck on it?

1524
01:03:25,201 --> 01:03:26,202
He can.

1525
01:03:26,269 --> 01:03:27,670
It's working.

1526
01:03:27,737 --> 01:03:28,971
-Can you suck on it?
-Hurry up!

1527
01:03:29,038 --> 01:03:30,139
Can you suck on it or not?

1528
01:03:30,206 --> 01:03:32,642
I can!

1529
01:03:33,810 --> 01:03:35,511
He can suck on it.

1530
01:03:35,578 --> 01:03:38,948
-Yes, Poong. He can suck on it! Hurry!
-Hurry up!

1531
01:03:39,015 --> 01:03:40,016
You can suck on it.

1532
01:03:40,082 --> 01:03:42,018
The moment I suck it,
you must close your esophagus right away!

1533
01:03:43,119 --> 01:03:45,221
-Is it too much?
-It hits my throat!

1534
01:03:45,288 --> 01:03:47,690
-It flies in?
-You have to be careful!

1535
01:03:47,757 --> 01:03:51,227
-They go on the noodles!
-What is that?

1536
01:03:52,762 --> 01:03:55,198
What is that? You have 50 seconds!

1537
01:03:55,264 --> 01:03:57,366
I've had that snack when I was younger.

1538
01:03:58,201 --> 01:04:01,304
FABRI FINISHES UP THE DESSERT

1539
01:04:05,007 --> 01:04:07,777
-What is that? You have 50 seconds!
-What?

1540
01:04:07,844 --> 01:04:11,881
-Fabri is busy with dessert!
-He's making dessert!

1541
01:04:11,948 --> 01:04:15,351
-He hasn't used the duck.
-Fabri, the duck!

1542
01:04:15,418 --> 01:04:16,886
-The carbonara.
-Forty seconds!

1543
01:04:18,187 --> 01:04:21,557
Fabri looks busy.
He's making dessert right now.

1544
01:04:21,624 --> 01:04:24,260
Aren't you going to use the duck?

1545
01:04:24,327 --> 01:04:26,262
Forty seconds!

1546
01:04:26,329 --> 01:04:27,630
A BIG SMILE

1547
01:04:27,697 --> 01:04:29,131
-What is that?
-Poong!

1548
01:04:29,699 --> 01:04:31,834
RED NOODLES AND A BLUE UMBRELLA

1549
01:04:31,901 --> 01:04:34,070
Poong finished first.

1550
01:04:34,136 --> 01:04:35,805
-He's done.
-The umbrella.

1551
01:04:35,872 --> 01:04:38,975
Look at the colors.
He made it look like a cocktail.

1552
01:04:39,041 --> 01:04:40,042
Right here!

1553
01:04:40,109 --> 01:04:42,345
-Poong finished!
-He's done.

1554
01:04:42,411 --> 01:04:44,180
-Look at that umbrella.
-Fabri!

1555
01:04:45,147 --> 01:04:46,315
NEXT, THE DUCK

1556
01:04:46,382 --> 01:04:47,884
-You have 20 seconds!
-Fabri.

1557
01:04:47,950 --> 01:04:50,519
-Fabri, you're running out of time.
-You can do this!

1558
01:04:50,586 --> 01:04:51,988
Chilled-bonara.

1559
01:04:52,054 --> 01:04:53,589
-Where is it?
-Chilled-bonara.

1560
01:04:53,656 --> 01:04:57,093
-He's almost done.
-The cheese.

1561
01:04:57,159 --> 01:05:00,496
-Ten seconds. Nine. Eight.
-Nine. Eight.

1562
01:05:00,563 --> 01:05:03,699
-Seven. Six. Five.
-Seven. Six. Five.

1563
01:05:03,766 --> 01:05:05,801
-Four. Three.
-Four. Three.

1564
01:05:05,868 --> 01:05:08,070
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

1565
01:05:08,137 --> 01:05:11,240
-Time's up, Fabri.
-He's done.

1566
01:05:11,307 --> 01:05:12,675
Fabri finished too.

1567
01:05:12,742 --> 01:05:14,410
-It was a wonderful battle.
-Yes.

1568
01:05:16,279 --> 01:05:18,080
Korea versus Italy.

1569
01:05:18,147 --> 01:05:19,615
That was a great fight.

1570
01:05:19,682 --> 01:05:22,184
He made a course meal.

1571
01:05:22,251 --> 01:05:24,787
-Isn't the difference too big?
-It's like a café.

1572
01:05:26,522 --> 01:05:28,858
And now, the two are

1573
01:05:28,925 --> 01:05:32,595
done cooking energy-recharging dishes
for Nam-il the vacuum cleaner.

1574
01:05:32,662 --> 01:05:35,064
Why the long face? What's wrong?

1575
01:05:35,131 --> 01:05:37,600
Is it because of The Gentleman Sucks?

1576
01:05:37,667 --> 01:05:39,402
We're all thinking the same thing.

1577
01:05:40,836 --> 01:05:42,538
You may get a dopamine hit
after you try it.

1578
01:05:42,605 --> 01:05:44,840
-Of course. You never know.
-It looks good.

1579
01:05:45,608 --> 01:05:49,946
RESUMMON THE LUNG CAPACITY
FROM HIS 2002 VACUUM CLEANER DAYS!

1580
01:05:50,913 --> 01:05:54,850
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
THE GENTLEMAN SUCKS

1581
01:05:54,917 --> 01:05:56,352
Is there a way to eat this?

1582
01:05:56,419 --> 01:05:58,220
-Just suck on it.
-Suck on it?

1583
01:05:58,287 --> 01:06:00,389
You can use the stick and get the meat.

1584
01:06:00,456 --> 01:06:05,561
I got the idea
from how Hiddink used to train you.

1585
01:06:05,628 --> 01:06:06,963
It may feel difficult today.

1586
01:06:07,029 --> 01:06:09,665
-But you'll be stronger tomorrow.
-I see.

1587
01:06:09,732 --> 01:06:11,000
He has a point.

1588
01:06:11,067 --> 01:06:13,769
What if he has a tough day today
and gets hospitalized tomorrow?

1589
01:06:13,836 --> 01:06:16,105
-It's decorated like a parfait.
-Parfait.

1590
01:06:16,172 --> 01:06:17,673
It will make you nostalgic.

1591
01:06:17,740 --> 01:06:20,443
-It'll increase your lung capacity.
-It's like working out.

1592
01:06:20,509 --> 01:06:22,211
Okay.

1593
01:06:22,278 --> 01:06:23,713
-Suck it.
-Yes.

1594
01:06:23,779 --> 01:06:25,214
-Suck it.
-Okay.

1595
01:06:25,281 --> 01:06:26,916
I hope he can suck it.

1596
01:06:26,983 --> 01:06:30,486
Now, can Nam-il suck it in
like a vacuum cleaner?

1597
01:06:30,553 --> 01:06:31,721
-It's going up.
-He's doing it.

1598
01:06:31,787 --> 01:06:33,589
-It's going up!
-It's going up!

1599
01:06:33,656 --> 01:06:36,726
-It's going up!
-It's coming.

1600
01:06:36,792 --> 01:06:39,862
I can see it rising up!

1601
01:06:39,929 --> 01:06:41,998
It's going up! It's going up again!

1602
01:06:42,064 --> 01:06:44,233
It's going up! It's going up again!

1603
01:06:44,300 --> 01:06:46,669
The vacuum cleaner sucks it in.

1604
01:06:46,736 --> 01:06:48,838
It's going up! It's going up again!

1605
01:06:48,904 --> 01:06:51,340
The vacuum cleaner sucks it in.

1606
01:06:51,407 --> 01:06:52,808
Is it too salty?

1607
01:06:54,643 --> 01:06:56,545
POONG-DINK IS DEEPLY SATISFIED

1608
01:06:56,612 --> 01:06:58,814
He could suck it in.

1609
01:06:58,881 --> 01:07:00,416
I'm dizzy.

1610
01:07:00,483 --> 01:07:02,952
-You sucked it in.
-It went up.

1611
01:07:03,019 --> 01:07:05,087
Keep sucking.

1612
01:07:05,154 --> 01:07:08,190
-He tries to suck it in again.
-Yes, that's it. Keep going.

1613
01:07:08,257 --> 01:07:09,558
The vacuum cleaner!

1614
01:07:09,625 --> 01:07:13,295
It's going up. He's sucking on it.

1615
01:07:13,362 --> 01:07:15,598
-It keeps going up.
-He's better than I thought.

1616
01:07:15,664 --> 01:07:17,600
The Gentleman Sucks!

1617
01:07:17,666 --> 01:07:19,268
Suck it, Nam-il!

1618
01:07:19,869 --> 01:07:21,771
THE 12TH PLAYER'S CHEER
GIVES HIM

1619
01:07:21,837 --> 01:07:23,039
THE FIGHTING SPIRIT

1620
01:07:23,105 --> 01:07:24,273
Suck it in!

1621
01:07:25,474 --> 01:07:28,844
He got one strand out at the end.

1622
01:07:28,911 --> 01:07:31,147
-You only lost your temper.
-You look drained.

1623
01:07:31,213 --> 01:07:33,282
Can I finish this before the day's over?

1624
01:07:33,349 --> 01:07:34,350
It won't decrease.

1625
01:07:34,417 --> 01:07:36,085
You'll be that much stronger
as soon as you finish it.

1626
01:07:36,152 --> 01:07:38,621
It'll give him two hearts.

1627
01:07:38,687 --> 01:07:40,289
-Should I try the meat?
-Yes, try it.

1628
01:07:40,356 --> 01:07:42,124
You can pick it up with the umbrella.

1629
01:07:42,191 --> 01:07:45,795
-It'll be easier to eat it with a fork.
-Nam-il looks drained.

1630
01:07:45,861 --> 01:07:47,596
He tries the pork.

1631
01:07:47,663 --> 01:07:50,199
-The meat must be nice.
-Yes.

1632
01:07:50,266 --> 01:07:52,001
-The meat must be good.
-Yes, it's cooked nicely.

1633
01:07:52,068 --> 01:07:53,235
It's cooked nicely.

1634
01:07:53,302 --> 01:07:57,706
First, the noodles you sucked on.

1635
01:07:57,773 --> 01:08:00,309
I asked to help me recharge my energy,

1636
01:08:00,376 --> 01:08:03,012
but I thought this was draining.

1637
01:08:03,079 --> 01:08:05,181
-Did you get drained?
-It took a lot of energy.

1638
01:08:05,247 --> 01:08:06,649
I see.

1639
01:08:06,715 --> 01:08:08,117
SUCKS TEETH

1640
01:08:08,184 --> 01:08:11,787
-And it's a bit bland too.
-Is it bland?

1641
01:08:11,854 --> 01:08:14,090
I think the straw
stops the sauce from coming up.

1642
01:08:14,156 --> 01:08:16,926
-I get it.
-Because the noodles stick to each other.

1643
01:08:16,992 --> 01:08:19,662
I only get the noodles
because the sauce stays in the middle.

1644
01:08:19,728 --> 01:08:21,564
They stick to each other
and lose the sauce.

1645
01:08:21,630 --> 01:08:23,332
Why don't you try it with a fork?

1646
01:08:23,399 --> 01:08:25,267
That's all for today's training.

1647
01:08:25,334 --> 01:08:27,269
You can relax and eat it with a fork.

1648
01:08:27,336 --> 01:08:30,239
-That's all for the training.
-You can try the meat too.

1649
01:08:30,306 --> 01:08:33,442
He's now eating it with a fork,
in Nam-il's style.

1650
01:08:33,509 --> 01:08:35,878
He tries the noodles
and the meat together.

1651
01:08:35,945 --> 01:08:38,581
-This is what I'm talking about.
-That's how you eat noodles.

1652
01:08:38,647 --> 01:08:39,849
-Mmm.
-Hey.

1653
01:08:40,850 --> 01:08:43,419
-What's wrong? Was that it?
-Yes.

1654
01:08:43,486 --> 01:08:45,988
He's like, "Why is this good?"

1655
01:08:46,055 --> 01:08:49,024
Is it different?
It's different from the straw.

1656
01:08:49,091 --> 01:08:51,160
-This is much better.
-Fork worked much better.

1657
01:08:51,227 --> 01:08:53,129
-That's true.
-Did you make him learn that skill?

1658
01:08:53,195 --> 01:08:54,630
You're right. He had to be trained hard.

1659
01:08:54,697 --> 01:08:56,165
That's how Hiddink manages his team.

1660
01:08:56,232 --> 01:08:58,868
-Train like it's the real game.
-He trains them very hard.

1661
01:08:58,934 --> 01:09:01,737
I can eat the noodles with the pork
when I use the fork,

1662
01:09:01,804 --> 01:09:02,972
and I like the combination.

1663
01:09:03,038 --> 01:09:04,273
I see.

1664
01:09:04,340 --> 01:09:07,910
You said you wanted to lose your temper,
and then get the dopamine hit.

1665
01:09:07,977 --> 01:09:10,179
First, temper, then, the dopamine.

1666
01:09:10,246 --> 01:09:14,016
You make him hungry first,
then you make him enjoy the food.

1667
01:09:14,083 --> 01:09:16,452
-It's good when he gets the dopamine hit.
-Yes.

1668
01:09:16,519 --> 01:09:18,053
That's Poong-dink.

1669
01:09:18,120 --> 01:09:21,690
-It's pretty good.
-It is?

1670
01:09:21,757 --> 01:09:23,292
POONG-DINK'S MAGIC CONTINUES

1671
01:09:23,359 --> 01:09:25,127
Poong-dink's uppercut!

1672
01:09:25,194 --> 01:09:28,631
<i>And next, Fabri from Italy's</i>
<i>Chilled-bonara.</i>

1673
01:09:30,032 --> 01:09:32,735
SERVED WITH HEALTHY DESSERT
AND SALAD

1674
01:09:33,536 --> 01:09:36,939
CHEF FABRI'S CHILLED-BONARA

1675
01:09:37,006 --> 01:09:39,542
He's standing with the soup.

1676
01:09:39,608 --> 01:09:42,011
-I'm curious.
-I can't even imagine.

1677
01:09:42,077 --> 01:09:43,579
It's white kimchi water and eggs.

1678
01:09:43,646 --> 01:09:46,682
-It's lukewarm.
-Lukewarm.

1679
01:09:46,749 --> 01:09:49,585
-It's pretty thick.
-You have the right thickness.

1680
01:09:49,652 --> 01:09:51,420
-It looks great.
-Doesn't it?

1681
01:09:51,487 --> 01:09:53,689
It looks overwhelmingly great.

1682
01:09:53,756 --> 01:09:56,725
Please mix it, then.

1683
01:09:56,792 --> 01:09:57,793
Where do I begin?

1684
01:09:57,860 --> 01:09:59,261
The main dish,

1685
01:09:59,328 --> 01:10:00,863
the side dish,

1686
01:10:00,930 --> 01:10:03,232
and last, the dessert.

1687
01:10:03,299 --> 01:10:04,800
-This is…
-It looks good.

1688
01:10:04,867 --> 01:10:09,305
The sauce is lukewarm, not too hot.

1689
01:10:10,072 --> 01:10:11,907
HE DIGS IN WITHOUT HESITATING

1690
01:10:11,974 --> 01:10:13,542
That's chilled carbonara.

1691
01:10:13,609 --> 01:10:16,679
He's been trained well.
He's good at sucking it in.

1692
01:10:16,745 --> 01:10:17,780
He's good at sucking it in.

1693
01:10:17,846 --> 01:10:22,084
-The Hiddink-style training.
-He's good at sucking the noodles in.

1694
01:10:22,751 --> 01:10:25,020
You keep talking with your eyes.
Can you just say it?

1695
01:10:25,087 --> 01:10:26,755
How did he make this flavor?

1696
01:10:27,523 --> 01:10:30,359
-What's it like?
-It doesn't seem like buckwheat noodles.

1697
01:10:30,426 --> 01:10:32,461
-Then?
-It's just like pasta.

1698
01:10:32,528 --> 01:10:34,063
-Like pasta?
-Pasta?

1699
01:10:34,129 --> 01:10:37,266
So it's unlike
the usual buckwheat noodles?

1700
01:10:37,333 --> 01:10:40,469
So does it taste like carbonara?

1701
01:10:40,536 --> 01:10:43,272
Buckwheat noodles are
less glutinous than regular noodles,

1702
01:10:43,339 --> 01:10:45,841
so they tend to break apart easily.

1703
01:10:45,908 --> 01:10:48,043
But that creamy sauce

1704
01:10:48,110 --> 01:10:50,846
-probably adds to that texture.
-I see.

1705
01:10:50,913 --> 01:10:52,715
He keeps eating the noodles.

1706
01:10:52,781 --> 01:10:55,217
-Oh, my.
-It must be really good.

1707
01:10:56,986 --> 01:10:58,921
HE SUCKS IN THE NOODLES
LIKE THE FORMER VACUUM CLEANER

1708
01:10:58,988 --> 01:11:01,690
It looks like Italy has the upper hand.

1709
01:11:01,757 --> 01:11:04,760
This time, he tries the side dish.

1710
01:11:05,694 --> 01:11:07,630
He eats it so well.

1711
01:11:07,696 --> 01:11:10,099
-Gosh.
-He's amazed.

1712
01:11:10,165 --> 01:11:11,867
First, he used white kimchi.

1713
01:11:11,934 --> 01:11:15,504
This white kimchi was a brilliant choice.

1714
01:11:15,571 --> 01:11:17,506
<i>Not only does it add texture,</i>

1715
01:11:17,573 --> 01:11:19,575
<i>but the fragrant fruit adds to the flavor.</i>

1716
01:11:19,642 --> 01:11:23,946
So it's a lot of fun
to enjoy the flavors in my mouth.

1717
01:11:24,013 --> 01:11:28,117
You might think the noodles are better
because Poong trained you

1718
01:11:28,183 --> 01:11:29,952
just before you tried that.

1719
01:11:30,019 --> 01:11:31,954
Do not forget his contribution.

1720
01:11:32,021 --> 01:11:34,089
-That's how he trained.
-Yes.

1721
01:11:34,156 --> 01:11:36,025
We don't know who'll win, though.
The dessert.

1722
01:11:36,091 --> 01:11:37,559
What did you put in here?

1723
01:11:37,626 --> 01:11:40,029
Yogurt, Chinese yams, and a banana.

1724
01:11:40,095 --> 01:11:42,298
-He used Chinese yams.
-And strawberries.

1725
01:11:42,364 --> 01:11:43,365
He grabs the bowl.

1726
01:11:43,432 --> 01:11:46,168
He grabs the bowl
as soon as he hears "Chinese yams."

1727
01:11:46,235 --> 01:11:48,871
-It looks great with granola.
-It's made with Chinese yams.

1728
01:11:48,937 --> 01:11:53,142
Look how he sucks it all in.
He's the vacuum cleaner.

1729
01:11:53,208 --> 01:11:55,144
-It's over.
-He shows a thumbs-up.

1730
01:11:55,210 --> 01:11:57,513
-Fabri won.
-It's over.

1731
01:11:57,579 --> 01:11:59,081
Can you taste the Chinese yams?

1732
01:11:59,148 --> 01:12:01,617
-I see.
-Does it go well with everything?

1733
01:12:01,684 --> 01:12:02,685
It's sticky.

1734
01:12:02,751 --> 01:12:05,321
Chinese yams have that stickiness.

1735
01:12:05,387 --> 01:12:06,822
Do you want to suck it in again?

1736
01:12:06,889 --> 01:12:09,858
-The vacuum cleaner!
-Nam-il!

1737
01:12:09,925 --> 01:12:12,961
Yes, that's it.

1738
01:12:13,028 --> 01:12:14,763
-It's so good.
-Was it?

1739
01:12:14,830 --> 01:12:16,265
Any complaints?

1740
01:12:17,032 --> 01:12:19,401
-No. It was perfect.
-Really?

1741
01:12:19,468 --> 01:12:22,004
-He's sucking it in again.
-He's sucking it in.

1742
01:12:22,071 --> 01:12:23,906
The vacuum cleaner!

1743
01:12:23,972 --> 01:12:26,275
THE VACUUM CLEANER
IS FULLY CHARGED

1744
01:12:26,342 --> 01:12:27,476
No, Korea just lost.

1745
01:12:27,543 --> 01:12:30,279
-The combination was great too.
-I see.

1746
01:12:30,346 --> 01:12:32,147
-Why don't we all suck it?
-Okay.

1747
01:12:32,214 --> 01:12:33,349
Let's all shout it together.

1748
01:12:33,415 --> 01:12:36,352
-The Gentleman Sucks!
-Sucks!

1749
01:12:37,019 --> 01:12:39,154
-Can you suck on it?
-Can you?

1750
01:12:39,221 --> 01:12:40,222
It's pretty easy.

1751
01:12:40,289 --> 01:12:41,890
SLURPING

1752
01:12:42,558 --> 01:12:46,228
THE ASMR OF THE CHEFS SUCKING

1753
01:12:47,429 --> 01:12:48,731
POONG-DINK IS TOUCHED

1754
01:12:49,231 --> 01:12:52,201
-The sound.
-You used the wrong dish.

1755
01:12:52,267 --> 01:12:54,603
It's easy to suck it in
when the bowl is bigger.

1756
01:12:54,670 --> 01:12:55,671
It's good.

1757
01:12:55,738 --> 01:12:56,705
-It is.
-It's so good.

1758
01:12:56,772 --> 01:12:58,240
It's good.

1759
01:12:58,307 --> 01:12:59,308
Why is this good?

1760
01:12:59,375 --> 01:13:01,877
It's like that
cup noodle version of spaghetti.

1761
01:13:01,944 --> 01:13:05,614
<i>It's mainly made with tomato sauce,</i>
<i>so it's great for your health.</i>

1762
01:13:05,681 --> 01:13:07,249
<i>-It's good.</i>
<i>-Yes, it's good.</i>

1763
01:13:07,316 --> 01:13:08,484
<i>It has a certain edge.</i>

1764
01:13:08,550 --> 01:13:09,918
It's fun to eat.

1765
01:13:11,053 --> 01:13:13,288
-I can see the appeal.
-Me too.

1766
01:13:13,355 --> 01:13:15,391
-Gosh.
-It wasn't so bad.

1767
01:13:15,457 --> 01:13:17,459
The meat is really savory.

1768
01:13:17,526 --> 01:13:19,361
-It's good.
-I like the texture.

1769
01:13:19,428 --> 01:13:21,296
<i>-The meat wasn't burnt.</i>
<i>-No.</i>

1770
01:13:21,363 --> 01:13:23,832
<i>-He cooked it evenly.</i>
<i>-It's good.</i>

1771
01:13:23,899 --> 01:13:25,601
<i>-It's good.</i>
<i>-It wasn't so bad.</i>

1772
01:13:25,667 --> 01:13:28,237
If the straw had been bigger,

1773
01:13:28,303 --> 01:13:30,906
the world would've changed.

1774
01:13:30,973 --> 01:13:33,609
I had a bigger straw ready.

1775
01:13:33,675 --> 01:13:38,881
But I wanted to resummon
his vacuum cleaner self from 2002.

1776
01:13:38,947 --> 01:13:40,482
That was why.

1777
01:13:40,549 --> 01:13:42,284
-I get it.
-You couldn't make it easy for him.

1778
01:13:42,351 --> 01:13:45,354
And now, let's try the carbonara.

1779
01:13:45,421 --> 01:13:50,559
I was curious about the sauce.
The mix of eggs and kimchi juice.

1780
01:13:50,626 --> 01:13:56,198
Yes, Italian soccer players eat eggs
and cheese to get more energy.

1781
01:13:56,265 --> 01:14:00,836
I was a bit unsure
about cold carbonara in my head.

1782
01:14:00,903 --> 01:14:02,171
It's so new.

1783
01:14:02,237 --> 01:14:04,940
When I took a bite,
I tasted the egg yolks,

1784
01:14:05,007 --> 01:14:07,876
<i>and I loved how it felt when it was mixed</i>
<i>with the buckwheat noodles.</i>

1785
01:14:07,943 --> 01:14:09,545
First of all,

1786
01:14:09,611 --> 01:14:10,913
as an honorary Italian…

1787
01:14:11,480 --> 01:14:14,650
-Tell us about it.
-You're a fake.

1788
01:14:14,716 --> 01:14:18,520
Italians are very sensitive
about carbonara.

1789
01:14:18,587 --> 01:14:19,888
It's their tradition.

1790
01:14:19,955 --> 01:14:23,592
<i>But he adeptly reinterpreted it</i>
<i>in a Korean style.</i>

1791
01:14:23,659 --> 01:14:28,864
If I closed my eyes, I wouldn't be able
to tell if it was carbonara or duck.

1792
01:14:28,931 --> 01:14:31,767
-It was wonderful.
-I see.

1793
01:14:31,834 --> 01:14:33,902
It's now time to choose.

1794
01:14:33,969 --> 01:14:37,473
Referee Nam-il,
this was the Again 2002 round.

1795
01:14:37,539 --> 01:14:39,208
Press one for Fabri,

1796
01:14:39,274 --> 01:14:41,043
press two for Poong.

1797
01:14:41,109 --> 01:14:44,046
Make your decision and press the button!

1798
01:14:44,112 --> 01:14:45,414
I really can't tell.

1799
01:14:45,981 --> 01:14:47,182
CONFLICTED

1800
01:14:47,249 --> 01:14:48,884
I have no idea.

1801
01:14:48,951 --> 01:14:53,155
No, it's hard to guess his choice.

1802
01:14:53,222 --> 01:14:56,291
It's hard to predict what he'll do
after what he did in round one.

1803
01:14:56,358 --> 01:14:58,961
-Did you make your choice? You did.
-I did.

1804
01:14:59,027 --> 01:15:01,497
Let's find out who Nam-il picked!

1805
01:15:01,563 --> 01:15:06,034
This round was called
again 2002, recharge the vacuum cleaner.

1806
01:15:06,101 --> 01:15:08,237
Will it be Kim Poong the Red Devil?

1807
01:15:08,303 --> 01:15:10,372
Or will it be <i>Gli Azzurri</i>, Fabri?

1808
01:15:10,439 --> 01:15:13,475
It's a return match
between Korea and Italy!

1809
01:15:13,542 --> 01:15:17,446
Who is the winner
here at <i>Chef & My Fridge </i>Stadium?

1810
01:15:17,513 --> 01:15:20,315
Who did Nam-il choose?

1811
01:15:20,382 --> 01:15:21,383
Who is it?

1812
01:15:21,450 --> 01:15:23,352
Who's the winner?

1813
01:15:25,721 --> 01:15:27,823
WHOA

1814
01:15:27,890 --> 01:15:29,892
Who's the winner?

1815
01:15:29,958 --> 01:15:31,126
Who is it?

1816
01:15:31,193 --> 01:15:32,928
FABRI WINS

1817
01:15:32,995 --> 01:15:35,564
CHEF FABRI'S CHILLED-BONARA WINS

1818
01:15:35,631 --> 01:15:39,434
-Italy wins. Fabri takes the win.
-Goal!

1819
01:15:39,501 --> 01:15:41,770
Italy gets their revenge.

1820
01:15:41,837 --> 01:15:45,274
-Gosh, he chose Italy.
-Come on.

1821
01:15:45,340 --> 01:15:48,544
I think I finally understand

1822
01:15:48,610 --> 01:15:52,180
where the Italian national team,
Gli Azzurri, gets their power.

1823
01:15:53,115 --> 01:15:57,185
The moment I ate it, I could feel
the energy with that dopamine hit.

1824
01:15:57,252 --> 01:15:58,387
It hit me like that.

1825
01:15:58,453 --> 01:16:00,322
-So it helped you recharge better.
-Yes.

1826
01:16:00,389 --> 01:16:02,457
-And lastly, this dessert.
-The dessert.

1827
01:16:02,524 --> 01:16:04,893
I loved this so much.

1828
01:16:06,795 --> 01:16:09,631
But Poong-dink trained you with the straw.

1829
01:16:09,698 --> 01:16:11,400
Excuse me, Poong-dink?

1830
01:16:11,466 --> 01:16:13,502
Just call him Poong-Dung Beetle.

1831
01:16:13,569 --> 01:16:15,604
Did the straw training not help?

1832
01:16:15,671 --> 01:16:17,940
It'll be delicious
if I eat it as a delicacy.

1833
01:16:18,006 --> 01:16:22,044
But there was a bit of a problem
with the container.

1834
01:16:22,110 --> 01:16:23,745
-You're right.
-Yes.

1835
01:16:23,812 --> 01:16:28,550
This means
Italy takes their revenge on Korea.

1836
01:16:28,617 --> 01:16:30,519
Hey, Fabri!

1837
01:16:31,086 --> 01:16:33,322
KNEELING CELEBRATION

1838
01:16:33,388 --> 01:16:35,457
This is his second win!

1839
01:16:35,524 --> 01:16:36,959
Congratulations, Fabri.

1840
01:16:37,025 --> 01:16:40,195
He seized his victory against Poong.

1841
01:16:40,262 --> 01:16:41,330
Great work.

1842
01:16:42,097 --> 01:16:43,799
Congratulations.

1843
01:16:43,865 --> 01:16:46,068
Dong-gook has seven people in his family.

1844
01:16:46,134 --> 01:16:48,370
We spend 17 million won
on just delivery food alone.

1845
01:16:48,437 --> 01:16:50,172
<i>It's like a school cafeteria.</i>

1846
01:16:50,238 --> 01:16:52,207
-But nothing in here is what I like.
-No, you're right.

1847
01:16:52,274 --> 01:16:54,443
I'll bring it up,
but everything gets ignored.

1848
01:16:54,509 --> 01:16:55,877
THE SAD REALITY OF A KOREAN DAD

1849
01:16:55,944 --> 01:16:57,346
I found eels.

1850
01:16:57,412 --> 01:16:59,147
I went out and got those on purpose.

1851
01:16:59,214 --> 01:17:01,550
The things I usually couldn't eat.

1852
01:17:01,617 --> 01:17:04,252
This round is only for Dong-gook.

1853
01:17:04,319 --> 01:17:06,722
<i>-I'm less nervous than before.</i>
<i>-He's less nervous.</i>

1854
01:17:06,788 --> 01:17:09,191
<i>I'll get Chef Hyun-suk's revenge.</i>

1855
01:17:09,257 --> 01:17:10,759
-He's definitely Little Hyun-suk.
-Yes.

1856
01:17:10,826 --> 01:17:12,394
He gestured to me to try it.

1857
01:17:12,461 --> 01:17:15,097
Look at how he's chopping.
He's asking for attention.

1858
01:17:15,163 --> 01:17:16,665
WHO WILL DONG-GOOK CHOOSE?

1859
01:17:16,732 --> 01:17:19,134
This is yet another return match.

1860
01:17:19,201 --> 01:17:22,938
-There it is! The eels!
-Cut them into big pieces.

1861
01:17:23,005 --> 01:17:25,240
<i>I've won against him,</i>
<i>so I didn't feel much pressure.</i>

1862
01:17:25,307 --> 01:17:26,475
Does that go into the soup?

1863
01:17:27,442 --> 01:17:28,644
I couldn't hear you!

1864
01:17:29,645 --> 01:17:31,113
My gosh! Help!

1865
01:17:31,179 --> 01:17:33,248
It's hot. It looks hot.

1866
01:17:33,315 --> 01:17:35,083
<i>-It looks hot.</i>
<i>-It's hot.</i>

1867
01:17:35,150 --> 01:17:37,052
His vacuum cleaner is on.

1868
01:17:37,119 --> 01:17:41,256
-Poong brought him back last week.
-I did that to him!

1869
01:17:50,599 --> 01:17:55,604
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
